{"term":"1957","caseName":"United States v. City of Detroit","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1957/26","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - November 14, 1957 (Part 2)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13427","transcript":[{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":0,"stop":18.846,"duration":18.85}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes Your Honor.","start":18.846,"stop":19.514,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":19.514,"stop":25.63,"duration":6.12}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":25.63,"stop":26.4,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now all (Inaudible)","start":26.4,"stop":33.277,"duration":6.88}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":33.277,"stop":34.975,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But no (Inaudible) enter into regularly the assessment phase (Inaudible)","start":34.975,"stop":51.275,"duration":16.3}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Only lands that come in under this Act 189.","start":51.275,"stop":53.761,"duration":2.49}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) and I gather that given (Inaudible) lease, let's say for a 20-year lease the tax (Inaudible) the City tax rate (Inaudible) $1000000, is that right?","start":53.761,"stop":82.691,"duration":28.93}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Lumped in with a whole assessment valuation.","start":82.691,"stop":86.008,"duration":3.32}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":86.008,"stop":86.599,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":86.599,"stop":87.664,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now if another 20-year lease on that property (Inaudible)","start":87.664,"stop":109.417,"duration":21.75}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes in proportion for the amount of property he is using.","start":109.417,"stop":114.429,"duration":5.01}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well Mr. O'Connor do you have two rolls, do you have a personal property roll and a real property tax roll?","start":114.429,"stop":121.195,"duration":6.77}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes we do Mr. Justice Warren.","start":121.195,"stop":123.723,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Then how does this get on your real property roll, I notice this exhibit says City of Detroit personal property assessment roll.","start":123.723,"stop":133.269,"duration":9.55},{"text":"Now that's different, how do you put it on --","start":133.269,"stop":137.535,"duration":4.27}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"It's very well taken Your Honor please --","start":137.535,"stop":138.154,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- formally here and then put it no your real property.","start":138.154,"stop":143.117,"duration":4.96}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"For lack of a better placed put it, I would, you know, as the answer.","start":143.117,"stop":148.504,"duration":5.39},{"text":"We use this and noted on this roll, leased land building Act 189 PA 1953 to distinguish the properties on this roll from properties that would be on the general personal property assessment role and subject to the general personal property assessment taxes.","start":148.504,"stop":173.926,"duration":25.42},{"text":"We merely use this form and placed on this form that notation, and that notation also was included in the bill, tax bill that was sent to the lessee so that he was -- he could not possibly under -- by any stretch of imagination conclude that this was on the personal property assessment roll subject to general personal property assessment laws, but was subject to the provisions of Act 189, which merely taxes the use.","start":173.926,"stop":207.92,"duration":33.99}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well then is this a third kind of a roll, you have your real estate roll and you have your personal property tax roll and is this a third kind of tax roll?","start":207.92,"stop":221.466,"duration":13.55}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"You might call it that Your Honor.","start":221.466,"stop":223.487,"duration":2.02},{"text":"The act was -- the act was new, and when we were starting to --","start":223.487,"stop":227.371,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I am not criticizing and I am just trying to find out but what I wanted to ask you because I should maybe have understood you, but I didn't.","start":227.371,"stop":236.417,"duration":9.05},{"text":"I do want to know if these pieces of property that are on in this Exhibit 97 are included in your real property roll for the purpose of fixing your real property rate?","start":236.417,"stop":251.842,"duration":15.43}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"They are Your Honor.","start":251.842,"stop":252.759,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"They are, all right, that's all.","start":252.759,"stop":255.058,"duration":2.3}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is this another way of getting out Mr. O'Connor let's take the first one, this Borg-Warner, if Borg-Warner owned that property instead of leasing it, but actually owned it, it would have an assessment as the owner of $352,060, wouldn't it?","start":255.058,"stop":271.86,"duration":16.8}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":271.86,"stop":272.733,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And that would have a tax bill at the tax rate against the $352,000?","start":272.733,"stop":278.874,"duration":6.14}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":278.874,"stop":279.722,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And the tax bill would be a real estate tax bill wouldn't it, if it owned the property?","start":279.722,"stop":285.992,"duration":6.27}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"With this notation --","start":285.992,"stop":287.587,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No I am -- assuming a different case, assuming it owned the property, not leased it but owned it, is that right?","start":287.587,"stop":294.489,"duration":6.9}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct Mr. Justice --","start":294.489,"stop":295.327,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It would get a real estate tax bill and an assessment of $352,000 at the local rate, is that so?","start":295.327,"stop":301.806,"duration":6.48}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":301.806,"stop":302.501,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now because it's the lessee of the property it gets what, a different kind of tax bill, a different color maybe or something?","start":302.501,"stop":312.382,"duration":9.88}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"I think frankly they are using the same, same bills that they've used in connection with general personal property tax.","start":312.382,"stop":320.539,"duration":8.16}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah so that --","start":320.539,"stop":321.182,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"What this notation contained on it --","start":321.182,"stop":323.491,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It gets, it gets a -- whatever it maybe called it's still a tax bill and then the assessment of $352,060 at the local rates for 1954.","start":323.491,"stop":335.144,"duration":11.65}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct Your Honor and of course as I have previously said the value of the United States property maybe used as a measure of the tax and the privilege under the cases that I have cited in my brief and I believe mentioned a short while ago.","start":335.144,"stop":352.86,"duration":17.72}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Have you cited any of the interstate commerce cases which have held that immune interstate trade can have a tax levied against it measured by the total value of the interstate trade?","start":352.86,"stop":372.736,"duration":19.88}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"No Mr. Justice Black I have not, but I have cited Plummer versus Coler for example which is an inheritance or succession tax which uses the full value of the United States bonds, which were included in the estate as a measure of the tax of the inheritance or succession tax and the Court concluded -- this Court concluded that that tax was not on the bonds of the United States which are -- were exempt from taxation, but is on the privilege of inheritance or succession.","start":372.736,"stop":410.143,"duration":37.41},{"text":"Now in connection with the Home Insurance Company case, which was a New York case, that involved a franchise tax, measured by the dividends and capital stock of the corporation.","start":410.143,"stop":422.785,"duration":12.64},{"text":"Included in the capital stock of the corporation were United States bonds which of course were tax exempt.","start":422.785,"stop":431.947,"duration":9.16},{"text":"They were included as a measure, the value of those bonds along with other properties of the corporation were included as a measure of the tax on the franchise, which the Court said could be done.","start":431.947,"stop":447.529,"duration":15.58},{"text":"It was not a tax on the bonds but on the franchise, the privilege of the business of the company conducting business.","start":447.529,"stop":457.503,"duration":9.97}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"When you challenge the tax on the basis of it being excessive by reason of the way it's measured or the only challenge to it is based on immunity?","start":457.503,"stop":467.941,"duration":10.44}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"The only challenge is based on immunity.","start":467.941,"stop":471.683,"duration":3.74}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Because the argument is, it's like Miller and Milwaukee, now what do you do with that?","start":471.683,"stop":478.905,"duration":7.22}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Miller versus Milwaukee if Your Honor please the tax the -- Miller owned dividends in a Milwaukee corporation.","start":478.905,"stop":492.035,"duration":13.13},{"text":"The Wisconsin statute provided for a tax on everything except United States bonds.","start":492.035,"stop":503.954,"duration":11.92},{"text":"They were accepted from the privilege tax from that case in measuring the privilege tax.","start":503.954,"stop":512.412,"duration":8.46},{"text":"When the dividends were paid out to Mr. Miller, the stockholder, the Wisconsin statute further provided that he should be taxed on those dividends only to the extent of the United States bonds, the value of the United States bonds and the Court held, and rightfully so in that case if Your Honors please, that that statute was specifically aimed at the United States bonds.","start":512.412,"stop":542.892,"duration":30.48},{"text":"Now of course that case did not -- well as I recall a franchise or privilege tax.","start":542.892,"stop":555.32,"duration":12.43},{"text":"Yes the Miller case did not involve a franchise or privilege tax or but an income tax.","start":555.32,"stop":560.874,"duration":5.55},{"text":"Now Macallen versus Massachusetts which government counsel cite in their brief as controlling of the situation, the statute accepted interest from United States bonds and determined that income for purposes of measuring the franchise tax on domestic corporations.","start":560.874,"stop":581.017,"duration":20.14},{"text":"The statute was later amended to include tax exempt securities in the measure of the franchise tax.","start":581.017,"stop":587.579,"duration":6.56},{"text":"So that amendment was specifically aimed at the United States bonds.","start":587.579,"stop":595.281,"duration":7.7},{"text":"Now the Court --","start":595.281,"stop":596.739,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Aren't you here specifically aiming at government derived property interest, a government derived interest?","start":596.739,"stop":604.901,"duration":8.16}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":604.901,"stop":605.533,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Does it make it any less so that you also cover some other exemption?","start":605.533,"stop":611.061,"duration":5.53},{"text":"Does that change the character of the general proposition of Miller against Milwaukee, namely that if you want to bring that pigeon down, you can't do it, it doesn't make a difference whether you bring the pigeon down from front or back?","start":611.061,"stop":631.505,"duration":20.44}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct Your Honor if the --","start":631.505,"stop":633.423,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the argument, isn't it?","start":633.423,"stop":634.02,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"If the statute is aimed at the United States bonds and is not specifically, then it's an invalid tax.","start":634.02,"stop":643.438,"duration":9.42},{"text":"Now of course in our case we contend that it is not aimed at the United States --","start":643.438,"stop":647.396,"duration":3.96}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Because you also hit other pigeons.","start":647.396,"stop":650.215,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon?","start":650.215,"stop":650.703,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Because you also hit the exemptions of Michigan (Inaudible)","start":650.703,"stop":654.187,"duration":3.48}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":654.187,"stop":655.566,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And religious institutions.","start":655.566,"stop":656.792,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct Mr. Justice Black.","start":656.792,"stop":658.929,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"So it gets down to a question largely on that point, does it not, of whether there is a discriminatory classification?","start":658.929,"stop":666.91,"duration":7.98}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"That's very true.","start":666.91,"stop":667.92,"duration":1.01},{"text":"In Carmichael versus Southern Coal & Coke Company which I've cited at page 28 of my brief and from which I quote says this in connection with the tax and classes and with reference to exemptions, there are exemptions provided in this Act, 189 which I will later discuss.","start":667.92,"stop":693.535,"duration":25.62},{"text":"Carmichael versus Southern Coal Company decided by this Court in 1937, and I quote therefrom as follows.","start":693.535,"stop":700.492,"duration":6.96},{"text":"“It is inherent in the exercise of the power to tax that a state be free to select the subjects of taxation and to grant exemptions.","start":700.492,"stop":708.951,"duration":8.46},{"text":"Neither Due Process nor Equal Protection imposes upon a state any rigid rule of equality of taxation.","start":708.951,"stop":717.288,"duration":8.34},{"text":"This Court has repeatedly held that inequalities which result from a singling out of one particular class for taxation or exemptions infringe no constitutional limitation, citing many cases.","start":717.288,"stop":732.198,"duration":14.91},{"text":"Like considerations govern exemptions from the operation of a tax imposed upon the members of the class.","start":732.198,"stop":738.794,"duration":6.6},{"text":"A legislature is not bound to tax every member of a class or not.","start":738.794,"stop":743.867,"duration":5.07},{"text":"It may make distinctions of degree, having a rational basis and when subjected to judicial scrutiny, they must be presumed to rest on that basis if there is any conceivable state of facts which would support it.","start":743.867,"stop":758.331,"duration":14.46}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Are there any exemptions in your statute?","start":758.331,"stop":762.107,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon?","start":762.107,"stop":762.791,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Are there any exemptions in your statute that seek out any members of the particular class that rent tax immune property?","start":762.791,"stop":773.399,"duration":10.61}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"A property of any state --","start":773.399,"stop":774.684,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It would include -- is that a complete classification?","start":774.684,"stop":778.175,"duration":3.49}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"A property of any state supported education institution is one of the exemptions in Act 189.","start":778.175,"stop":784.855,"duration":6.68}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You have one.","start":784.855,"stop":785.597,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, there are two others and the two are these, where the use is by way of a concession in or relative to use of a public airport, park, market, fairground or other similar property, which is available to the use of the general public and one more.","start":785.597,"stop":802.426,"duration":16.83},{"text":"In the case of federal property for which payments are made in lieu of taxes in amounts equivalent to taxes which might otherwise be a lawfully assessed.","start":802.426,"stop":812.966,"duration":10.54},{"text":"Those provisions appear I believe in Section 1 of Act 189.","start":812.966,"stop":818.237,"duration":5.27}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose Mr. O' Connor instead of this compendious provision, what's the number of this statute 104?","start":818.237,"stop":825.649,"duration":7.41}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"189.","start":825.649,"stop":826.361,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"189, suppose instead of in the form -- suppose instead of in the form in which we have it, Section 1 said all leaseholds from government immune, federal government immune properties, shall be assessed on the value of the property for the privilege of having such a leasehold.","start":826.361,"stop":848.844,"duration":22.48},{"text":"Section 2, all leaseholds that were immune from taxation, because owned by the State of Michigan shall be assessed, shall be taxed to the full value of such immunized state property.","start":848.844,"stop":865.059,"duration":16.21},{"text":"Section 3, all property derived and owned by cities on lease, et cetera in Section 4, all property of charitable religious organizations enjoying immunity as such, all of the statutes are like that, four sections, putting in all the categories of property as such exempt for taxing the privilege of having a leasehold thereof.","start":865.059,"stop":891.025,"duration":25.97},{"text":"Would you be making the same argument?","start":891.025,"stop":893.696,"duration":2.67}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say this, if Your Honor please?","start":893.696,"stop":898.892,"duration":5.2},{"text":"As we know and as government counsel has pointed out, Section 6 of the Military Leasing Act of 1947 provides for the taxation of the lessee's interest, as far as local taxing agencies are concerned.","start":898.892,"stop":916.173,"duration":17.28},{"text":"Now, I think we would have that right regardless of that provision, but we say here, we are not taxing the lessee's interest.","start":916.173,"stop":924.889,"duration":8.72},{"text":"If we tax the lessee's interest, then we would, under the language in the Allegheny case, be required to evaluate the lessee's interest in property in accordance with regularly accepted methods of appraisal such as taking into consideration then term of the lease, the termination provisions in the lease, the amount of rent and so forth.","start":924.889,"stop":951.056,"duration":26.17},{"text":"Now we obviously didn't do that.","start":951.056,"stop":955.806,"duration":4.75},{"text":"We based this tax upon the true cash value of the property.","start":955.806,"stop":962.085,"duration":6.28},{"text":"Furthermore, if we were to tax the lessee's interest, rather than the privilege of using the property, the legislature could never have accomplished the result intended, namely to eliminate a discrimination between lessees of private and public property and put them on an equal footing for the reason that, the lessee's interest would only amount to an infinitesimal part of the money that can be received in the fashion the legislature tax provided in this Act.","start":962.085,"stop":999.589,"duration":37.5},{"text":"Now as I say the legislature could have imposed a much larger sum.","start":999.589,"stop":1004.071,"duration":4.48},{"text":"The fact that it is equal to the tax on the property, does not make it a tax on the property because again as I say, a specific tax and of course a specific tax as Your Honors know is nothing but an excise tax and examples of which are occupation taxes, privilege taxes and license taxes.","start":1004.071,"stop":1030.074,"duration":26},{"text":"Those taxes were placed upon the lessee's use of the property in connection with business conducted for profit, to put the lessees on an equal basis, lessees of private or public property.","start":1030.074,"stop":1049.531,"duration":19.46},{"text":"For example, corporation A coming into the State of Michigan desires to lease property, defines that I have a parcel of real estate, a private person, and it finds the government has a parcel of real estate.","start":1049.531,"stop":1064.923,"duration":15.39},{"text":"Both parcels meet their specifications to perfection, which parcel will this corporation rent, certainly not mine because they know if they rent mine, they are going to have to pay taxes either in the amount of the rent charged or in addition to the rent charged in consideration over reduction in that rent and in that respect it's very discriminatory and it was that very thing that the legislature sought to eliminate in passing this Act.","start":1064.923,"stop":1102.916,"duration":37.99},{"text":"Now Flint versus Stone Tracy was a situation where the federal government sought to tax franchises of corporations in various states based upon and measured by the income of the corporation, including municipally tax exempt bonds.","start":1102.916,"stop":1124.019,"duration":21.1},{"text":"Now the federal government did not grant those franchises.","start":1124.019,"stop":1130.178,"duration":6.16},{"text":"If the federal government can do that in connection with state franchises not granted by it, then certainly the states ought to be able to tax a privilege of using which arises out of an instrument namely the lease of the federal government.","start":1130.178,"stop":1148.827,"duration":18.65},{"text":"The fact that the privilege of using the property is exercised within the jurisdiction of the state of Michigan is sufficient in and of itself alone to permit the state to tax, and I have covered that point in my brief wherein I say in connection with Home Insurance Company case which quotes from Savings versus (Inaudible) nothing can be more certain in legal decision and that the privileges and franchises of a private corporation of all trades and avocations by which the citizens acquire a livelihood maybe taxed by a state for the support of the state government.","start":1148.827,"stop":1183.37,"duration":34.54},{"text":"Authority to that affect resides in the state independent of the federal government and is wholly unaffected by the fact that the corporation or individual has or has not made an investment in federal securities.","start":1183.37,"stop":1198.058,"duration":14.69},{"text":"One other point I would like to raise, counsel for the government refers the Senate Committee hearings and refers to Section 6 of the Military Leasing Act, we say it does not apply because we are not taxing the lessee's interest.","start":1198.058,"stop":1211.224,"duration":13.17},{"text":"The Military Leasing Act does not prohibit the taxing of a privilege of using the property.","start":1211.224,"stop":1216.165,"duration":4.94},{"text":"There was no discussions in the Senate Committee hearings in connections with the privilege of using the property and while the army and navy as I gather from a reading of the Senate Report, were both interested in seeing that properties leased by the government for commercial purposes should be taxed in order to eliminate that discrimination that was ever present between public and private lessees, they were not able to arrive at any legal basis for doing it.","start":1216.165,"stop":1243.664,"duration":27.5},{"text":"As one of the senators I recall said, when it was suggested that you transfer title of the government to the lessee during the term of the lease, one of the senators said I don't think that would be constitutional because you cannot place ownership in a person that actually doesn't own the property by a congressional act, therefore they forgot it, decided to leave it to general legislation but as a last measure passed Section 6 of the Military Leasing Act which only infinitesimally helps in the situation to avoid discrimination.","start":1243.664,"stop":1278.047,"duration":34.38},{"text":"It doesn't, because you don't get the same results as you would from a lessee of private property.","start":1278.047,"stop":1292.722,"duration":14.67},{"text":"I see my time is up if Your Honors please, Mr. Street will finish.","start":1292.722,"stop":1307.306,"duration":14.58}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Street.","start":1307.306,"stop":1309.163,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Harold M. Street","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, please the Court?","start":1309.163,"stop":1312.199,"duration":3.04},{"text":"I don't want labor this too long, but there are a few issues that are unique to a particular situation being Continental Motors Corporation located in Muskegon, County; and a few points that I would like to attempt to clarify.","start":1312.199,"stop":1331.865,"duration":19.67},{"text":"It's quite apparent from reading opposing counsel's brief that they refuse to make a distinction between a property tax and a privilege tax, refuse to concede that this might conceivably be a privilege tax rather that a property tax and treat it that way throughout in both their original brief and their reply brief.","start":1331.865,"stop":1355.326,"duration":23.46},{"text":"I might say our reply brief, the reply brief was only received yesterday, I will try to cover it in oral argument to save filing a reply to the reply if we can do so.","start":1355.326,"stop":1367.686,"duration":12.36},{"text":"I think it will clarify the picture somewhat if we point out some of the instances in which Act 189 does not apply.","start":1367.686,"stop":1376.634,"duration":8.95},{"text":"Post office is a prime example.","start":1376.634,"stop":1378.233,"duration":1.6},{"text":"It could never apply to a post office.","start":1378.233,"stop":1380.906,"duration":2.67},{"text":"There is so much made in the footnote of the reply brief that it might apply to the Pentagon building, that Virginia might tax the Secretary for occupying the Pentagon building.","start":1380.906,"stop":1392.419,"duration":11.51},{"text":"Of course that could never happen under one Act 189 and I don't think it could happen under any other the very simple reason he is not a private individual or corporation who is using the property in connection with a business conducted for profit.","start":1392.419,"stop":1406.657,"duration":14.24},{"text":"So the same is of course true of an army camp, marine base; any installation of a sort that's not used for profit it could never apply.","start":1406.657,"stop":1416.79,"duration":10.13},{"text":"Some reference has been made to forest preserves, grazing lands, I might point out too, if those are public lands, open to the public in the nature of the park and the government grants a privilege by way of a concession to someone to graze those lands, it again would not come within the Act, because of the express exception as long as that land is again open to use by the public and that's an important feature of the Act.","start":1416.79,"stop":1445.224,"duration":28.43},{"text":"We have a forest preserve in Michigan and perhaps we can explain this a little more clearly as to just what might happen.","start":1445.224,"stop":1451.705,"duration":6.48},{"text":"The (Inaudible) Forest Preserve is a short distance north of Muskegon.","start":1451.705,"stop":1456.312,"duration":4.61},{"text":"It is not taxable.","start":1456.312,"stop":1457.338,"duration":1.03},{"text":"It places some burdens upon our local government but certainly not unreasonable burdens and we don't care to tax it.","start":1457.338,"stop":1464.587,"duration":7.25},{"text":"But what if the government should lease that land to be timbered?","start":1464.587,"stop":1469.307,"duration":4.72},{"text":"We know what happens in Michigan well enough, when such leases are made, a large mill is brought in that brings in hundreds of employees and they bring their families, they must be housed, their children must be schooled, roads must be built and fire protection afforded.","start":1469.307,"stop":1487.706,"duration":18.4},{"text":"Then we have an entirely different situation.","start":1487.706,"stop":1490.53,"duration":2.82},{"text":"I say that private entrepreneur, who is harvesting the trees from that land for profit should be taxed on his privilege and this Court has held that he maybe taxed.","start":1490.53,"stop":1505.168,"duration":14.64},{"text":"I'd like to refer to Wilson versus Cook, where there was an Arkansas statute which imposed a privilege on anyone engaged in the business of severing from the soil for commercial purposes, natural resources including timber.","start":1505.168,"stop":1521.788,"duration":16.62},{"text":"Now in this particular instance, it was a forest preserve.","start":1521.788,"stop":1525.511,"duration":3.72},{"text":"The trees belong to the United States Government as well as the land.","start":1525.511,"stop":1530.059,"duration":4.55},{"text":"This man was given a contract to sever the trees.","start":1530.059,"stop":1535.147,"duration":5.09},{"text":"He enjoyed a privilege granted exclusively by the federal government to harvest these trees yet a severance tax imposed by the state of Arkansas was upheld by this Court on the basis of James versus Dravo and other cases.","start":1535.147,"stop":1553.981,"duration":18.83},{"text":"Act 189 would affect substantially the same thing in this case, if these forest preserves were leased for that purpose and it's only just that it should do so.","start":1553.981,"stop":1568.224,"duration":14.24},{"text":"There is some claim that Continental stands in a little different status here than Borg-Warner, because Borg-Warner is manufacturing automobile parts for profit, while Continental is confined to manufacturing tank engines for the army corps.","start":1568.224,"stop":1583.724,"duration":15.5},{"text":"There is some difference on the surface, there it's true.","start":1583.724,"stop":1587.617,"duration":3.89},{"text":"You want to keep in mind however that Continental is competition Chrysler, General Motors and Ford who also like to make engines and who are at a distinct disadvantage in competing with Continental.","start":1587.617,"stop":1600.044,"duration":12.43},{"text":"We don't mind that in Muskegon, but I say in the long-run anything that removes this spur of free competition is going to work detrimental to this government who may think temporarily they are getting a bargain by giving Continental the plant, rent free and tax free.","start":1600.044,"stop":1620.342,"duration":20.3},{"text":"Claim is also made the Continental because of this unusual situation is an agent or instrumentality of the government then they sure of course should be tax exempt.","start":1620.342,"stop":1631.884,"duration":11.54},{"text":"That situation I think is covered in the case cited in my brief of Henneford versus Silas Mason and I don't know if I need to elaborate it further here.","start":1631.884,"stop":1642.911,"duration":11.03},{"text":"That same contention was made in lower court and ultimately abandoned on appeal, but what if we did even for the sake argument concede that Continental in this particular case is an agent or instrumentality of the federal government?","start":1642.911,"stop":1656.742,"duration":13.83},{"text":"Does it afford an immunity under the decisions of this Court?","start":1656.742,"stop":1660.783,"duration":4.04},{"text":"I might point out that in United States versus California which is of course familiar to you and is included in an ALR citation on my brief.","start":1660.783,"stop":1671.646,"duration":10.86},{"text":"In referring to this restriction or immunity says it's equally a restriction on taxation by either of the instrumentalities of the other.","start":1671.646,"stop":1682.892,"duration":11.25},{"text":"The state instrumentalities supposedly enjoy the same privilege.","start":1682.892,"stop":1689.425,"duration":6.53},{"text":"But what have been some of the decisions?","start":1689.425,"stop":1693.414,"duration":3.99},{"text":"The early case of South Carolina followed up later by Ohio verus Helvering where the state owned liquor, sold it through its own dispensaries.","start":1693.414,"stop":1704.046,"duration":10.63},{"text":"This Court imposed a privilege tax upon the sale of that liquor and held it valid.","start":1704.046,"stop":1710.597,"duration":6.55},{"text":"The Court used this rather colorful language, when the state enters the marketplace seeking customers, it divests itself of its quasi-sovereignty pro tanto.","start":1710.597,"stop":1721.043,"duration":10.45},{"text":"Even more closely at home when the State of New York owning the Saratoga Springs attempted to sell water through its own public commission, the federal government imposed a tax of $0.02 per gallon upon the water, and this Court sustained the tax saying that it is clear that where a state engages in a business in competition with private enterprise, it enjoys no special privilege or immunity.","start":1721.043,"stop":1747.43,"duration":26.39},{"text":"And even closer to home is Allen versus University System where Georgia setup a state commission to operate the University of Georgia and Georgia Tech and they were held liable for their admission tax to the football games, though conceding that, that was a part of an educational function and that education was a proper function of the state, yet that tax was imposed and sustained.","start":1747.43,"stop":1773.386,"duration":25.96},{"text":"I don't believe first that Continental is an agent or instrumentality of the federal government, but if so because of its peculiar activity, I don't believe it's entitled to any immunity particularly.","start":1773.386,"stop":1785.174,"duration":11.79},{"text":"Now much is made here of the measure of tax.","start":1785.174,"stop":1787.526,"duration":2.35},{"text":"In fact it's about the only argument made against it, saying since it's measured on the basis of the value of the property, that is therefore amounts to a tax on the property itself.","start":1787.526,"stop":1802.429,"duration":14.9},{"text":"How could such a tax be measured and really be fair and just?","start":1802.429,"stop":1811.989,"duration":9.56},{"text":"It is suggested that perhaps if it were measured on something like oh we'll say in the case about the severance of trees on a board foot basis or in the Esso case where you sustained a tax of $0.06 per gallon on Esso for storing government owned gasoline, that perhaps if it were measured by gallons or something of that sort, it would be a different picture and wouldn't look like a tax on the property.","start":1811.989,"stop":1840.243,"duration":28.25},{"text":"But how can it be done?","start":1840.243,"stop":1841.179,"duration":0.94},{"text":"Acres is the only thing that might come to mind as being some standard of that sort but how would Acres apply to 3.5 acres upon which this $8 million plant rests in Muskegon County, why a tax of $10,000 per acre clearly would be reasonable?","start":1841.179,"stop":1860.336,"duration":19.16},{"text":"But there is for instance say 20 acre tract adjoining that's used as nothing but a testing ground, which is virtually vacant land, that land wouldn't be worth $200 an acre.","start":1860.336,"stop":1871.644,"duration":11.31},{"text":"And below that is a 3 acre parcel used to dump waste that's not worth $10 an acre, certainly you cannot arrive at a fair and just tax on any other basis than -- the measure that the State of Michigan sought it to imply here.","start":1871.644,"stop":1890.902,"duration":19.26},{"text":"Counsel's reply brief is directed at two things, the Military Leasing Act and the other.","start":1890.902,"stop":1897.754,"duration":6.85},{"text":"He has repeated over and over again that the uses included in the privilege I mean rather that the uses included in the lease, the privilege of uses included in the lease whether the lease be one year, five years or ten, the privilege of use is also included in ownership you want to keep in mind and it has been held that we can segregate the faggots and attach them separately.","start":1897.754,"stop":1923.625,"duration":25.87},{"text":"The burden of the argument there is that since the privilege of use is necessarily included within a lease or even ownership, it can never be taxed up to the same amount as a tax that might be imposed because of ownership or because of leasehold interest viewing it as a property right.","start":1923.625,"stop":1945.916,"duration":22.29},{"text":"Now that simply is not the case.","start":1945.916,"stop":1948.014,"duration":2.1},{"text":"In fact it maybe taxed far in excess of that amount.","start":1948.014,"stop":1952.093,"duration":4.08},{"text":"Just look at the gasoline stored by Esso Standard Oil for which they paid $0.06 a gallon for the privilege of storage.","start":1952.093,"stop":1961.068,"duration":8.97},{"text":"Now if Esso had owned that gasoline themselves and had it in their own tanks, they wouldn't have been subject to the tax because they would not have been engaged in the business of storing gasoline.","start":1961.068,"stop":1972.634,"duration":11.57},{"text":"They would have paid the regular ad valorem personal property tax by virtue of their ownership at the end of the year.","start":1972.634,"stop":1980.564,"duration":7.93},{"text":"What would it have amounted to, possibly 10, 15 mills.","start":1980.564,"stop":1985.057,"duration":4.49},{"text":"Six mills on gasoline worth possibly $0.30 or 0.35 a gallon, it's somewhere around a 150 mills.","start":1985.057,"stop":1993.889,"duration":8.83},{"text":"Now a man who owns furs and has them in a warehouse will pay an ad valorem personal property tax of a few mills on it each year.","start":1993.889,"stop":2003.143,"duration":9.25},{"text":"What if he elects to exercise his privilege which is included in his privilege of ownership of sale during a year, immediately a sales tax in Michigan of 3% or 30 mills is imposed.","start":2003.143,"stop":2018.446,"duration":15.3},{"text":"And his troubles are only beginning because the federal government then imposes a 10% tax which is a 100 mills because he exercised his privilege of sale which is included within his ownership, so that the tax upon a privilege may far exceed any tax that can be imposed because of ownership alone.","start":2018.446,"stop":2042.72,"duration":24.27},{"text":"In this instance it's merely made equal.","start":2042.72,"stop":2046.686,"duration":3.97},{"text":"The interesting part to me about this long reference to the Military Leasing Act lies in the debate that it is recognized that a serious injustice and inequality exists.","start":2046.686,"stop":2061.623,"duration":14.94},{"text":"The long years of debate that had gone on in the Senate and in Congress results really in nothing.","start":2061.623,"stop":2072.263,"duration":10.64},{"text":"We've labeled a mountain and come up with a mole hill here.","start":2072.263,"stop":2075.585,"duration":3.32},{"text":"They all say it's a serious problem.","start":2075.585,"stop":2077.667,"duration":2.08},{"text":"It's unjust.","start":2077.667,"stop":2078.422,"duration":0.76},{"text":"Something ought to be done, but what should be done?","start":2078.422,"stop":2081.495,"duration":3.07},{"text":"What can we do that will bring about a fair and just solution?","start":2081.495,"stop":2086.38,"duration":4.89},{"text":"The inference is they have virtually given up except for one thing they're going to resort to a federal dole in the payments, in what they call payments in lieu of taxes.","start":2086.38,"stop":2097.624,"duration":11.24},{"text":"Now some reference has been made to the fact that the school district I represent has been forced to accept some of those.","start":2097.624,"stop":2104.444,"duration":6.82},{"text":"It's immaterial here.","start":2104.444,"stop":2105.579,"duration":1.14},{"text":"It did not apply in the year 1940 – '54 and it did not receive any for that year.","start":2105.579,"stop":2112.371,"duration":6.79},{"text":"There has been a temporary act passed since which expires in '58 which for hire purposes will expire next year because hire tax for '57 isn't payable until '58.","start":2112.371,"stop":2124.345,"duration":11.97},{"text":"We may have one more year under that act but we don't know whether it would be extended or not.","start":2124.345,"stop":2129.514,"duration":5.17},{"text":"I think we'll all agree that this federal dole is certainly an unsatisfactory solution in any event.","start":2129.514,"stop":2135.19,"duration":5.68}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is this the general act that expires next year?","start":2135.19,"stop":2137.799,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"Harold M. Street","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah, it's general, quite broad in its scope at least it covers the Continental Plant.","start":2137.799,"stop":2143.208,"duration":5.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon me.","start":2143.208,"stop":2143.957,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Harold M. Street","textObjs":[{"text":"At least it covers the Continental Plant.","start":2143.957,"stop":2146.201,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the generality?","start":2146.201,"stop":2149.227,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Harold M. Street","textObjs":[{"text":"In this particular act, as I recall, it's land that formally belonged to the Reconstruction Finance Corporation and then fell into government hand –-","start":2149.227,"stop":2157.821,"duration":8.59}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It's all related to reconstruction finance?","start":2157.821,"stop":2160.896,"duration":3.08}]},{"speakerName":"Harold M. Street","textObjs":[{"text":"This particular act, as I recall it, it applies in hire case, there are other acts that do apply but they don't apply in all instances such as here in '54 there was no applicable act.","start":2160.896,"stop":2173.975,"duration":13.08},{"text":"Your Honors –-","start":2173.975,"stop":2174.566,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The presence of the applicable acts for leaseholds made today this year, are they covered by acts or are they all covered?","start":2174.566,"stop":2186.72,"duration":12.15}]},{"speakerName":"Harold M. Street","textObjs":[{"text":"I only suppose – I know there's Military Leasing Act and that of course would catch a small tax with a lease of one year or returnable at will and so on.","start":2186.72,"stop":2197.968,"duration":11.25},{"text":"The point I want to make here – well here was the main problem, as I had pointed out, you'll notice in Senate debate.","start":2197.968,"stop":2203.078,"duration":5.11},{"text":"One senator said, “Well let's transfer title over to these people and with a recapture clause, that will make it taxable and that will solve our problem.”","start":2203.078,"stop":2211.585,"duration":8.51},{"text":"Someone pointed out the situation and it was referred to here.","start":2211.585,"stop":2215.447,"duration":3.86},{"text":"The government may want to reserve a large part of that plant for storage and on the lease we'll say a third.","start":2215.447,"stop":2221.583,"duration":6.14},{"text":"Well the lessee if he is going to get taxed on the whole property, will like that.","start":2221.583,"stop":2225.99,"duration":4.41},{"text":"Act 189 takes care of that, it's only the property actually used, that's made available to and actually used.","start":2225.99,"stop":2232.91,"duration":6.92},{"text":"Now there was inference made that perhaps in the Borg-Warner case, space used for storage was included in the assessment.","start":2232.91,"stop":2239.718,"duration":6.81},{"text":"If so it was by error and could have been corrected, had it been called to the attention of the assessing officers I'm sure because that portion of the plant would not be used.","start":2239.718,"stop":2250.642,"duration":10.92},{"text":"Another problem what confronted them, what we might refer to as white elephant plant.","start":2250.642,"stop":2255.183,"duration":4.54},{"text":"Here is a big plant that costs millions of dollars to bill, we want it as a standby facility, it does not have too much value for commercial use and yet if we transfer title over, it will be taxable value.","start":2255.183,"stop":2269.346,"duration":14.16},{"text":"That's taken care of too in this sort of situation.","start":2269.346,"stop":2272.141,"duration":2.8},{"text":"Let's look at Continental Plant a value of $8 million cost.","start":2272.141,"stop":2275.995,"duration":3.85},{"text":"It's on the assessment rolls at 3 million.","start":2275.995,"stop":2277.856,"duration":1.86},{"text":"Our assessor recognizes and must assess property in the state Michigan on the basis of its present market value what it will bring on the market today, which equalizes something and copes with the problem that I say cannot be solved on a federal level.","start":2277.856,"stop":2296.663,"duration":18.81},{"text":"Now the whole attitude seems to have been here by opposing counsel will have -- the United States Congress has coped with this matter for a great many years and has not received a – obtained a solution which they might do sometime in the future but in the meantime let's get along with this dole or something we have done everything that can be done.","start":2296.663,"stop":2316.277,"duration":19.61},{"text":"Now with all due respect to the United States Congress I don't believe that they have a monopoly on wisdom.","start":2316.277,"stop":2322.73,"duration":6.45},{"text":"I think there's a little residual of wisdom left in the Michigan state legislature.","start":2322.73,"stop":2328.832,"duration":6.1},{"text":"And instead of debating on ad infinitum, the Michigan legislature has done something and the unique part of it here is no one comes here and says that this act is unfair to the United States government, that it's unfair to Continental Motors or to Borg-Warner or that it is unfair to anyone else.","start":2328.832,"stop":2349.696,"duration":20.86},{"text":"Most of the lower courts commented on the inherent justice and desirability of the act and no one has pointed out in any inherent evil.","start":2349.696,"stop":2362.585,"duration":12.89},{"text":"Some comment has been made that the act is a little inartistic and not sophisticated.","start":2362.585,"stop":2366.833,"duration":4.25},{"text":"I think that's one of its best merits.","start":2366.833,"stop":2369.109,"duration":2.28},{"text":"It's a very simple act.","start":2369.109,"stop":2371.368,"duration":2.26},{"text":"We make use of existing machinery that's already in operation.","start":2371.368,"stop":2376.383,"duration":5.01},{"text":"We don't have to set up a bureau with a lot of new elaborate employees to administer this act.","start":2376.383,"stop":2385.574,"duration":9.19},{"text":"It's simple in its operation, it's clear, it's understand – and it's equitable in its operation.","start":2385.574,"stop":2392.56,"duration":6.99},{"text":"Your Honor all we ask is this Court consider that in view of the reply brief, the action taken there, that it's entirely possible that the legislature of the State of Michigan in using this residue of wisdom that's left to them have solved a problem, at least on a local level, which I submit cannot be solved on a federal level.","start":2392.56,"stop":2418.466,"duration":25.91},{"text":"Thank you Your Honor.","start":2418.466,"stop":2419.055,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Street in your time to prove Muskegon, how do you assess this property?","start":2419.055,"stop":2425.095,"duration":6.04},{"text":"Do you assess it as personal property or does it go on the real property roll as we were told?","start":2425.095,"stop":2433.278,"duration":8.18}]},{"speakerName":"Harold M. Street","textObjs":[{"text":"This one slipped on the real property roll.","start":2433.278,"stop":2435.279,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Beg your pardon?","start":2435.279,"stop":2436.347,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Harold M. Street","textObjs":[{"text":"This one got on the real property roll.","start":2436.347,"stop":2440.378,"duration":4.03},{"text":"It was pointed this was a new Act, the assessors didn't know just what to do with it.","start":2440.378,"stop":2444.526,"duration":4.15},{"text":"In our township this property had been carried on the assessment roll right along you see until it was ultimately declared surplus and went through various channels and then in 1953 the year this Act became effective went to the United States as such.","start":2444.526,"stop":2461.443,"duration":16.92},{"text":"So the assessor already had it on his roll, so he simply went ahead and made an assessed value and set it down in this instance on the real property roll.","start":2461.443,"stop":2471.465,"duration":10.02},{"text":"It seems to me -- I don't see any substance to the difference, technically there probably should be a third roll setup for this type of property I believe.","start":2471.465,"stop":2480.19,"duration":8.72}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":2480.19,"stop":2481.631,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask Mr. Street.","start":2481.631,"stop":2483.313,"duration":1.68},{"text":"I gather in striking the tax rate, you aggregate both real property assessments and personal property tax assessments, don't you?","start":2483.313,"stop":2494.833,"duration":11.52}]},{"speakerName":"Harold M. Street","textObjs":[{"text":"This Act does not apply to personal property here.","start":2494.833,"stop":2497.032,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well no, I'm speaking generally.","start":2497.032,"stop":2499.314,"duration":2.28},{"text":"In striking the local tax rate, you have a uniform rate that applies both to real estate assessments and personal property tax assessments?","start":2499.314,"stop":2506.568,"duration":7.25}]},{"speakerName":"Harold M. Street","textObjs":[{"text":"It's the mechanics, the way it's done in Michigan is the assessor goes out and he evaluates all the property.","start":2506.568,"stop":2512.512,"duration":5.94}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Real or personal?","start":2512.512,"stop":2513.75,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Harold M. Street","textObjs":[{"text":"Real or personal, yes and then finds out what the school must, the county must have and so on and then it decides what millage must be applied to that valuation to produce the amount of money needed, that's the mechanics of it.","start":2513.75,"stop":2527.717,"duration":13.97}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So that you have the same rate, the consequence is you get the same rate, whether the tax is on personal property or on real property.","start":2527.717,"stop":2535.736,"duration":8.02}]},{"speakerName":"Harold M. Street","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that is correct.","start":2535.736,"stop":2536.437,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It's the same rate and then arriving at the rate you aggregate the assessments against real property and the assessments against personal property all together.","start":2536.437,"stop":2546.89,"duration":10.45}]},{"speakerName":"Harold M. Street","textObjs":[{"text":"We lump them all together, yes.","start":2546.89,"stop":2548.27,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And then wipe the rates from that.","start":2548.27,"stop":2550.067,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Harold M. Street","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":2550.067,"stop":2550.592,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So it doesn't practically make any difference whether this assessment is listed on a personal property tax roll or real estate tax roll or otherwise, does it?","start":2550.592,"stop":2559.185,"duration":8.59}]},{"speakerName":"Harold M. Street","textObjs":[{"text":"Not applied (Inaudible) to go on the third tax rule, it all comes out the same place, yes.","start":2559.185,"stop":2563.672,"duration":4.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Street you said several times this can't be dealt with by Congress, it must be dealt with locally.","start":2563.672,"stop":2569.927,"duration":6.26},{"text":"Now if that's so that for me at least could have a very important bearing on striking the adjustment between the state and federal authority, why do you say that?","start":2569.927,"stop":2579.259,"duration":9.33}]},{"speakerName":"Harold M. Street","textObjs":[{"text":"One, where the difficulty is pointed out, about the only way it could be done on a federal level would be to transfer this title back with a recapture clause.","start":2579.259,"stop":2587.365,"duration":8.11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But just an authorization by Congress so that each state do what Michigan tried to do would do it, wouldn't it?","start":2587.365,"stop":2593.223,"duration":5.86}]},{"speakerName":"Harold M. Street","textObjs":[{"text":"If they said that -- well you would get the same result though.","start":2593.223,"stop":2596.767,"duration":3.54},{"text":"Then you would be -- you will say de-immunizing all of these plants.","start":2596.767,"stop":2601.825,"duration":5.06},{"text":"In some instances --","start":2601.825,"stop":2603.017,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean it could exactly what it does about taxing bank staff, national bank staff.","start":2603.017,"stop":2607.535,"duration":4.52}]},{"speakerName":"Harold M. Street","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh it could, but I don't believe it would be a satisfactory --","start":2607.535,"stop":2610.27,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well why not?","start":2610.27,"stop":2611.444,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Harold M. Street","textObjs":[{"text":"Well if these difficulties like your white elephant plants that they fear or a plant where the government wants to retain portions of it, well say for storage and future use.","start":2611.444,"stop":2620.947,"duration":9.5},{"text":"If they de-immunize the whole thing so to speak it all becomes taxable, which maybe unjust to the federal government in certain ways.","start":2620.947,"stop":2627.517,"duration":6.57}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Why can't they make the same qualifications that you make, I don't follow?","start":2627.517,"stop":2632.794,"duration":5.28}]},{"speakerName":"Harold M. Street","textObjs":[{"text":"It's possible if they would say used in connection with the business conducted for profit such portions.","start":2632.794,"stop":2640.221,"duration":7.43},{"text":"If it could -- federal government adopted in substance 189 they might solve it Your Honor on the same level.","start":2640.221,"stop":2650.778,"duration":10.56},{"text":"Thank you.","start":2650.778,"stop":2652.764,"duration":1.99}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Fisher.","start":2652.764,"stop":2656.105,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court?","start":2656.105,"stop":2661.758,"duration":5.65},{"text":"The counsel for Muskegon Mr. Street has just agreed with us that the privilege of use is one of the bundles of rights that represent a property right.","start":2661.758,"stop":2676.2,"duration":14.44},{"text":"He has said that Michigan can take this one right of the property rights, the right to use and occupy, and they can tax that at the full value of the government's property.","start":2676.2,"stop":2689.631,"duration":13.43},{"text":"I believe in agreeing that right to use, privilege of use is one of the property rights, is the only property right that the lessee has.","start":2689.631,"stop":2699.66,"duration":10.03},{"text":"The extent of his right is measured by the lease.","start":2699.66,"stop":2702.531,"duration":2.87},{"text":"He is agreeing that the lessee's interest and the privilege of use are just the same thing, not only in substance, but analytically.","start":2702.531,"stop":2714.238,"duration":11.71},{"text":"There is no difference.","start":2714.238,"stop":2717.024,"duration":2.79},{"text":"I suggest that to my main argument that the privilege of use of lessee, the tax against property are the lessee's interest which they have.","start":2717.024,"stop":2726.465,"duration":9.44},{"text":"Congress, in the Military Leasing Act, said you can tax the value of the lessee's interest.","start":2726.465,"stop":2733.59,"duration":7.13},{"text":"We believe that certainly applies in the Borg-Warner case.","start":2733.59,"stop":2738.299,"duration":4.71},{"text":"The Supreme Court, this Court has for years gone through and considered the ramifications of federal immunity.","start":2738.299,"stop":2748.192,"duration":9.89},{"text":"It is a major substantive problem with which this Court has wrestled time and again.","start":2748.192,"stop":2753.468,"duration":5.28},{"text":"In no case and here I refer to Dravo, as well as the cases that followed it, in no case was it suggested that the full value of government owned property is subject to state taxation, provided the state changes the words.","start":2753.468,"stop":2767.959,"duration":14.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So it all gets down then to amounts, does it, because you must accept you rely on -- you talk about Macallen, I think the light is taken out of Macallen by educational film?","start":2767.959,"stop":2782.329,"duration":14.37}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"I'll a heavier foot on Miller and Milwaukee on that.","start":2782.329,"stop":2788.153,"duration":5.82},{"text":"Here the -- that's not the only thing, the measure is not the only thing bad about this tax.","start":2788.153,"stop":2792.73,"duration":4.58},{"text":"We believe this tax is directed aimed at federal property.","start":2792.73,"stop":2797.042,"duration":4.31},{"text":"Now they went through and showed there were four pieces of property in Detroit that has been assessed under this statute.","start":2797.042,"stop":2802.262,"duration":5.22},{"text":"98% of the valuation there listed is federally owned property.","start":2802.262,"stop":2807.092,"duration":4.83},{"text":"They have carried two pieces of property, one was $500 and one about $12,000.","start":2807.092,"stop":2811.218,"duration":4.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's because the facts found so, that doesn't prove sinister purpose.","start":2811.218,"stop":2815.927,"duration":4.71}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"It doesn't prove sinister purpose.","start":2815.927,"stop":2817.509,"duration":1.58},{"text":"It proves that the major substantive effect of this.","start":2817.509,"stop":2820.198,"duration":2.69},{"text":"Now the statute exempts all state aided educational institutions.","start":2820.198,"stop":2826.526,"duration":6.33},{"text":"They can lease out their property to the defense plant or to anyone else for profit and that lessee is not taxed.","start":2826.526,"stop":2836.995,"duration":10.47},{"text":"There is no tax on him, he is exempt, he gets the privilege of the state, although he is working for profit, everything else, this tax has been whittled down by the cutting out -- the major form of statement exempt institutions which do these properties, they educate large educational institutions and they -- I think the statute is very much like the one you suggested Your Honor where they said the federal property here, we will offer tax, a little state property, we get another little pigeon in this flock of ducks.","start":2836.995,"stop":2864.594,"duration":27.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well little, why do you say little?","start":2864.594,"stop":2866.341,"duration":1.75},{"text":"Suppose there were in Detroit religious institutions (Inaudible) like the Trinity Church in New York with vast holding and all of it exempt, would that change the legal problem?","start":2866.341,"stop":2883.058,"duration":16.72}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"It would change one aspect of the problem, it would remove the fact that this is -- we think it is directed primarily that of profit.","start":2883.058,"stop":2890.015,"duration":6.96}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But then you must -- then it does turn or the question of directive tort is decisive and you say derived from the fact that the bulk of the property which feels this tax happens to be or is, not to put in a question begging words, is federally exempt.","start":2890.015,"stop":2914.713,"duration":24.7},{"text":"You prove sinister purpose, do you prove design, this record against federal property otherwise and the fact that a lot of the property is federally exempt.","start":2914.713,"stop":2922.39,"duration":7.68}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"No, that was relied upon in the Macallen case explicitly by Justice Holmes speaking for the Court saying, certainly that one can be -- is the most conspicuous instance of exemption at the present time, that statute too covered the state ones and was much less direct.","start":2922.39,"stop":2936.524,"duration":14.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well they first had a statute which tried to reach it and then it didn't and -- but I put to you --","start":2936.524,"stop":2941.106,"duration":4.58}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"The state --","start":2941.106,"stop":2941.456,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- I put it to you that this isn't the Miller Milwaukee.","start":2941.456,"stop":2945.03,"duration":3.57}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2945.03,"stop":2945.326,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And I put it to you that Macallen really is -- is hardly breathing anymore.","start":2945.326,"stop":2953.789,"duration":8.46}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"We do not rely exclusively on that.","start":2953.789,"stop":2957.681,"duration":3.89},{"text":"The tax, the problem with which Congress and the Court have dealt is a major substantive problem.","start":2957.681,"stop":2964.496,"duration":6.82},{"text":"The burden on the locality is enormous, that burden is the same whether it's an air base, which has a lot of people going in there, whether it's a government run plant such as atomic energy plants might be run exclusively by government employees and non-taxable, the burden is the same whether a not for profit corporation moves in or whether a for profit corporation moves in.","start":2964.496,"stop":2986.853,"duration":22.36},{"text":"Now the weapon which Michigan is trying to deal with this substantive problem is saying that by changing six words, ten words, whatever the left statute is, by calling this a privilege tax, using a name that has been favored as a different kind of tax, we can take a property interest, the right to use this property, the lessee's property -- we can take the leasehold interest and we will say we are taxing that privilege of the lessee and then we, the whole federal immunity of government property is defeated.","start":2986.853,"stop":3017.808,"duration":30.95},{"text":"The substantive problem is just really it turns out they say, a matter of form.","start":3017.808,"stop":3021.703,"duration":3.89},{"text":"For a 100 years we thought that federal property is immune, but it turned out that states didn't know they could call a property interest a -- call a property interest a privilege and then measure the privilege by the whole property.","start":3021.703,"stop":3034.544,"duration":12.84},{"text":"In Allegheny they were taxing part of the property, the real estate measured by the whole property.","start":3034.544,"stop":3041.943,"duration":7.4},{"text":"This Court explicitly said you cannot do that.","start":3041.943,"stop":3044.791,"duration":2.85},{"text":"Even if you can tax the property you can tax, you cannot include in that property interest, the property interest of the United States.","start":3044.791,"stop":3052.621,"duration":7.83},{"text":"You cannot measure the value of --","start":3052.621,"stop":3055.022,"duration":2.4}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you believe that?","start":3055.022,"stop":3057.494,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe the language of the court although not necessarily the holding --","start":3057.494,"stop":3060.944,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I want to reserve your point of the taxation of -- the value of the leasehold income.","start":3060.944,"stop":3069.336,"duration":8.39}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"There you are dealing not with the leased interest in the government's machinery that was reserved, but real estate tax in Allegheny was on Mesta's plant measured by -- Mesta's plant plus the government machinery.","start":3069.336,"stop":3086.473,"duration":17.14},{"text":"The Court said the state has made no effort to segregate Mesta's interest in taxing.","start":3086.473,"stop":3092.469,"duration":6},{"text":"The full value of the property, including the whole ownership interest as well as whatever value proper appraisal might attribute to the leasehold, was included in Mesta's assessment.","start":3092.469,"stop":3102.864,"duration":10.39},{"text":"It is contented the whole value of the property maybe reached since the impact of the tax is upon Mesta.","start":3102.864,"stop":3109.698,"duration":6.83},{"text":"We think, however, that the government's property interest are not taxable either to it or to its bailee.","start":3109.698,"stop":3116.46,"duration":6.76},{"text":"They then went on referring to the fact that beneficial personal use of property maybe taxed and then the next sentence said that neither he, meaning the contractor nor the government can be taxed for the government's property interest.","start":3116.46,"stop":3131.367,"duration":14.91},{"text":"Now I do not believe that the reasoning of that case can stand up if this statute in Michigan is upheld.","start":3131.367,"stop":3139.466,"duration":8.1}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It seems to me there's a difference I concur in result (Inaudible) the state made no effort to segregate the two, here it maybe aborted effort, but the state has made an effort to tax nothing but (Inaudible) concerned the value of the leasehold in that case.","start":3139.466,"stop":3162.003,"duration":22.54},{"text":"Now it has fixed the value (Inaudible) raise of tax rate and one value of property, but do you say that fixing, having one factor value of the property -- deprived it of complete validity and (Inaudible).","start":3162.003,"stop":3185.959,"duration":23.96},{"text":"Suppose instead of fixing it using those two factors, it simply said whereas the real estate tax without saying, real estate tax of 2% we fix the tax on leasehold interest as 10% would that been unconstitutional?","start":3185.959,"stop":3202.777,"duration":16.82},{"text":"Supposing now that the government was not in, is there anything wrong with that?","start":3202.777,"stop":3208.303,"duration":5.53}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"There is nothing wrong with a tax of 10% on leasehold interest as such I suppose if it is fairly applied across the board to lessees of property and it appears it does not merely meant and in substance effect and operation a way of getting the real estate tax.","start":3208.303,"stop":3227.352,"duration":19.05},{"text":"I think that the tax immunity of the United States in this property which is government owned is a matter of a substance.","start":3227.352,"stop":3232.639,"duration":5.29},{"text":"I think that there are the tax of all federally owned property was subject to normal tax could be about $2 billion a year.","start":3232.639,"stop":3241.243,"duration":8.6},{"text":"If this were passed out it would be a bonanza to some communities which have no real services to the federally owned property they --","start":3241.243,"stop":3248.949,"duration":7.71}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Would that affect this lease, don't you have this problem here, what you argue now seems to me would be a question of classification not the question of the other, unless we can just simply infer from the fact that this tax be levied on property leased from government, federal or state or religious, where they have religious immunity, unless we can infer from that there is an invidious purpose to tax the property of the government.","start":3248.949,"stop":3277.218,"duration":28.27},{"text":"I agree with you, if we look at sum, but are you saying that looking in those circumstances we must reach the conclusion that this is a tax on government property and if so what goes with the Michigan tax law insofar as the attempt to tax property leasehold value of property owned by the state and by religious institutions?","start":3277.218,"stop":3302.154,"duration":24.94}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Well let's see if I can kind of answer that Your Honor.","start":3302.154,"stop":3305.246,"duration":3.09},{"text":"One argument which is this tax is plainly designed to offset tax immunity.","start":3305.246,"stop":3312.09,"duration":6.84},{"text":"Its conceited purpose is to offset the tax immunity of tax exempt property.","start":3312.09,"stop":3319.051,"duration":6.96},{"text":"The --","start":3319.051,"stop":3321.116,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the goal across the board --","start":3321.116,"stop":3323.955,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"This is --","start":3323.955,"stop":3324.699,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the whole board --","start":3324.699,"stop":3326.097,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"The purpose --","start":3326.097,"stop":3326.314,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of all tax exempt properties.","start":3326.314,"stop":3327.417,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Purpose is to remove the tax exemption of tax exempt properties.","start":3327.417,"stop":3333.641,"duration":6.22},{"text":"I say that Michigan has full power to remove the tax exemption of property which it makes tax exempt, but that by doing that it does not, because it decides to remove its own immunity which it creates, it might not have any tax immunity, it might decide not to have any local state laws, because it decides to remove its immunity does not give it a privilege of making an offsetting compensatory tax aimed at offsetting the federal tax immunity.","start":3333.641,"stop":3360.555,"duration":26.91},{"text":"And however much of Michigan's tax immunity they offset or decide to cancel out or not to cancel out, they are aiming a portion of their shot is solely for the tax exempt federal property and they can do what they want with Michigan but they cannot have a statute which grabs federal tax immune property and says, we have now got a new formula of words, it turns out we can remove this property because it is tax exempt.","start":3360.555,"stop":3390.667,"duration":30.11},{"text":"We can tax -- the incidence of the tax falls because the property is tax exempt.","start":3390.667,"stop":3394.834,"duration":4.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That is why they are taxing.","start":3394.834,"stop":3396.273,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"That's why they are --","start":3396.273,"stop":3397.367,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's why they are taxing.","start":3397.367,"stop":3399.119,"duration":1.75},{"text":"In order to equalize taxation of owners of property or manufacturers of property, they want to have every owner who enjoys a certain privilege, a certain source of power a part of his running expenses of the government.","start":3399.119,"stop":3415.538,"duration":16.42},{"text":"And they take care of all the other fellows by one form of taxation and they say you have a certain, you are given a certain power, you may have been given it by a certificate to have a water powered plant, you may have been given it because somebody left you some money and you have an estate tax or you may have been given it by the United States government and that is what we call in the law generally a license tax, a privilege tax.","start":3415.538,"stop":3443.436,"duration":27.9},{"text":"It isn't any to less privilege because (Inaudible) is the grant holder of the privilege and you can't cut under with reference to this particular type of privilege, the whole rate division of the tax law between taxing property because you own property and taxing -- in fact imposing a tax on a person, because all taxation falls on a person, it doesn't fall on the unanimous thing, it falls on person, because he is in possession of certain prerogative powers.","start":3443.436,"stop":3477.29,"duration":33.85}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor the privilege here is a property interest.","start":3477.29,"stop":3482.39,"duration":5.1},{"text":"The particular privilege which they call a privilege is not like being a corporation.","start":3482.39,"stop":3486.605,"duration":4.22},{"text":"It's not like engaging in a business of storing gasoline.","start":3486.605,"stop":3489.523,"duration":2.92},{"text":"The particular privilege they have picked out as a privilege tax is one of the property interests in the government property.","start":3489.523,"stop":3497.578,"duration":8.05},{"text":"It is -- I'll come back with the Secretary of Defense.","start":3497.578,"stop":3501.651,"duration":4.07},{"text":"It's a different thing to tax the Pentagon.","start":3501.651,"stop":3504.695,"duration":3.04},{"text":"It would be something else to tax him for the privilege of using the Pentagon and I would say that that he is paid a salary to use it, he is supposed -- there is no difference in private person.","start":3504.695,"stop":3516.9,"duration":12.2},{"text":"He is doing government business on government property for a pay and he has the privilege of occupying that property.","start":3516.9,"stop":3523.662,"duration":6.76},{"text":"This is the same thing that Continental is doing in the government plant in Muskegon.","start":3523.662,"stop":3528.452,"duration":4.79},{"text":"They are working for pay on government property doing the government's business of building tank engines.","start":3528.452,"stop":3535.733,"duration":7.28},{"text":"Now if -- I agree there is a distinction between privilege and property taxes, I do not – we submit we cannot take a property interest, a right of use, an occupancy of government property and call that privilege by just calling it a privilege.","start":3535.733,"stop":3549.159,"duration":13.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Fisher the Secretary of Defense or the postmaster in Detroit is an instrumentality of the government, but ever since Dravo you can no longer speak of any fellow who does work for the government of United States, an instrumentality.","start":3549.159,"stop":3564.871,"duration":15.71}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"The substantive problem, -- there are distinctions whether we paid put Oakridge on salaries or had a private contractor run it, the substantive problem is here that government plans have a major impact on local communities, a tremendous impact and there is appreciable problem.","start":3564.871,"stop":3585.081,"duration":20.21},{"text":"This problem is one with which Congress can deal because it alone can waive immunity of full government property where it caused an impact and of plants in which they have divided interest.","start":3585.081,"stop":3598.143,"duration":13.06},{"text":"It has expressly stated that the lessees maybe taxed for their interest up to the value of the leasehold interest.","start":3598.143,"stop":3605.78,"duration":7.64},{"text":"We believe that they can be tax no further.","start":3605.78,"stop":3607.942,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me ask you one other question excuse me, (Inaudible).","start":3607.942,"stop":3614.984,"duration":7.04},{"text":"Suppose the ones that disagree with you about this tax and think that this is a legitimate tax on a leasehold interest except your argument that we do not look into the words of the statute, we try to see just exactly how it functions, where does that put us in connection with the other two, other case if we accept the idea we do not look at labels, we do not look at names, but their taxes (Inaudible) the same preference in the State of Michigan as this one does, would it be consistent in your way of thinking on these cases to hold this tax valid and hold the others invalid?","start":3614.984,"stop":3662.435,"duration":47.45}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I -- even if Your Honors disagree with position we have presenting in this case, in these two cases, the Continental and Borg-Warner, I would believe that as to the Michigan personal property ad valorem tax on aircraft manufacturing in process and materials, that there the tax is a -- because of the property and there is no other instance that it falls on, it's not because of the use of the property.","start":3662.435,"stop":3697.018,"duration":34.58},{"text":"You might say that both --","start":3697.018,"stop":3698.072,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Just doing what you admonish us not to do here looking at the words that have been used (Inaudible) practically functions?","start":3698.072,"stop":3706.504,"duration":8.43}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- it's my position that you -- my position is that you should take a look at the substantive problem and deal with the fact for -- since at least for a long time this Court had held that federally owned property which is really officially owned by the United States cannot be taxed.","start":3706.504,"stop":3732.341,"duration":25.84},{"text":"I believe that you should say that a tax which is called a tax on that property on the first Michigan cases we were talking about the Murray case is clearly that once we find if you agree with us that the government at substantial beneficial ownership interest in those parts we have power to control over them.","start":3732.341,"stop":3752.259,"duration":19.92},{"text":"I think you should come to this case and say that they have taken a property interest, the right to use, which is one of the fundamental rights of the property and they have taken this property interest and said we will tax this property interest, which the occupant has by the value the entire property and that is not an appropriate measure of the privilege which these people of the use they are having of it I'd say.","start":3752.259,"stop":3780.542,"duration":28.28},{"text":"You are taking property interest and taxing by the whole property so I'd say that – we say that they're both bad.","start":3780.542,"stop":3786.698,"duration":6.16},{"text":"If you disagree in this case I think it'd be because of the line which Justice Frankfurter suggested that there is always been a distinction between a privilege tax and a property tax and it would be emphasizing the form that this is the tax on the right to use, the privilege of use and it would be because of that, that you would -- might disagree with us in this case, but if you adopt to that rule, it is because of the form of the tax it is good, you could not then say that Detroit personal property tax could be well applied to the government property.","start":3786.698,"stop":3824.949,"duration":38.25},{"text":"Thank you Your Honor I am sorry to --","start":3824.949,"stop":3826.55,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"It's alright.","start":3826.55,"stop":3837.627,"duration":11.08}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - November 14, 1957 (Part 1)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13510","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 26, United States of America and Borg-Warner Corporation, Appellants, versus City Of Detroit, a Municipal Corporation and number 37, United States of America versus Township of Muskegon, a Municipal Corporation.","start":0,"stop":18.462,"duration":18.46},{"text":"Mr. Fisher.","start":18.462,"stop":21.056,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court?","start":21.056,"stop":27.193,"duration":6.14},{"text":"These cases, here on appeal from the Supreme Court of Michigan, involved the validity of a Michigan Statute which explicitly imposes a special tax on the lessees and users of tax exempt property.","start":27.193,"stop":47.528,"duration":20.33},{"text":"You have three numbers, three cases here, number 26, to the United States and Borg-Warner against Detroit involves a defense plant which is owned by the United States and Detroit and leased to Borg-Warner.","start":47.528,"stop":62.629,"duration":15.1},{"text":"Number 37, number 38 are separate appeals by the United States and by Continental Motors involving a defense plant in Muskegon, Michigan which is owned by the United States and occupied and used by the Continental Motors Corporation.","start":62.629,"stop":83.346,"duration":20.72},{"text":"Although three cases are here consolidated for argument, you have only two, in substance two cases, the Muskegon case and the Detroit case that is the Continental case in Muskegon and the Borg-Warner case in Detroit.","start":83.346,"stop":100.312,"duration":16.97},{"text":"Unlike the case we just were arguing, there is no dispute about the ownership of this property or who owns it or what title means.","start":100.312,"stop":112.287,"duration":11.98},{"text":"Again unlike the (Inaudible) case, this is not a general tax levied on everybody equally in Michigan.","start":112.287,"stop":122.45,"duration":10.16},{"text":"The facts of the two cases are sufficiently different, so we will have to state them separately.","start":122.45,"stop":127.94,"duration":5.49},{"text":"The plant in Detroit is a naval industrial reserve plant owned by the United States for a number of years.","start":127.94,"stop":135.15,"duration":7.21},{"text":"In 1947, in the Military Leasing Act, Congress authorized long-term leases on defense plants which should be available on a standby basis which were not currently needed for defense production.","start":135.15,"stop":150.353,"duration":15.2},{"text":"Under a negotiated lease effective in 1948, dated 1950, this plant was leased to the Borg-Warner Corporation for five years, and options on their part to extend for three additional terms and five years each.","start":150.353,"stop":167.613,"duration":17.26},{"text":"The lease was revived and extended in 1958, until 1958 and 1953 effective till 1958.","start":167.613,"stop":177.921,"duration":10.31},{"text":"Under the lease, Borg-Warner leases the bulk, almost all of plant.","start":177.921,"stop":182.989,"duration":5.07},{"text":"This includes a storage area in which all the machine tools owned by the United States in the plant are stored and a manufacturing area in which Borg-Warner uses for its own private commercial purposes unconnected with national defense.","start":182.989,"stop":198.678,"duration":15.69},{"text":"Borg-Warner has a duty to maintain the storage area and to oil and grease and make sure the equipment there is in an operating, usable condition and upon termination of the lease Borg-Warner must reinstall all the machine tools back to their places in the manufacturing area and throughout the plant.","start":198.678,"stop":221.329,"duration":22.65},{"text":"The lease is subject to cancellation upon declaration of a national emergency by the President or upon 120 days notice by the Secretary of the Navy in the interest of national defense.","start":221.329,"stop":235.848,"duration":14.52},{"text":"In 1953, Michigan adopted Public Act number 189, an Act to provide for the taxation of lessees and users of tax exempt property.","start":235.848,"stop":248.675,"duration":12.83},{"text":"As of January 1, 1954, Detroit assessed the tax against Borg-Warner under this Act.","start":248.675,"stop":257.588,"duration":8.91},{"text":"The Board of Assessors valued the property precisely as it would have done had such real property been owned in free simple and occupied by Borg-Warner Corporation.","start":257.588,"stop":269.029,"duration":11.44},{"text":"That is the stipulation.","start":269.029,"stop":271.052,"duration":2.02},{"text":"They assessed this just as a real property tax assessment.","start":271.052,"stop":277.486,"duration":6.43},{"text":"Property was assessed at some $350,000 and the tax was something over $12,000 was imposed.","start":277.486,"stop":283.451,"duration":5.97},{"text":"Borg-Warner paid the tax under protest and on September 1954, the United States and Borg-Warner together joined in bringing suit as plaintiffs for a refund of the tax.","start":283.451,"stop":299.57,"duration":16.12},{"text":"At the time of the renewal of the lease, effective 1953 which was actually negotiated in 1954, the lease included a provision that United Sates would be responsible for this tax if it were valid, but that it would be contested and Borg-Warner would cooperate in contesting the validity of the tax, full burden of the tax if imposed or if recovered in this case, it subsequently felt benefits or hurts the United State.","start":299.57,"stop":328.711,"duration":29.14},{"text":"In the lower -- it was alleged that Act 189 was repugnant to the Constitution and that authorized taxation of property owned by the United States.","start":328.711,"stop":337.838,"duration":9.13},{"text":"Both the Circuit Court of Wayne County and the Supreme Court of Michigan upheld the statute.","start":337.838,"stop":345.434,"duration":7.6},{"text":"Supreme Court of Michigan stated the tax was not a tax on the property nor on the leasehold interest, but and I quote “A specific tax on the privilege of using the property.”","start":345.434,"stop":359.783,"duration":14.35},{"text":"United States and Borg-Warner both appealed to this Court, which noted probable jurisdiction.","start":359.783,"stop":365.713,"duration":5.93},{"text":"Numbers 37 and 38 involving the defense plant in Muskegon --","start":365.713,"stop":370.929,"duration":5.22}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Fisher may I ask how it is that the full burden of this tax falls on the government?","start":370.929,"stop":379.103,"duration":8.17}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"At the time when the first lease was negotiated, it was assumed the taxed property was not taxable and that there would be no tax equivalent to the real estate taxes imposed.","start":379.103,"stop":390.238,"duration":11.13},{"text":"The lease was negotiated on that terms.","start":390.238,"stop":392.583,"duration":2.35},{"text":"At each five-year interval the terms of lease are subject to renegotiation.","start":392.583,"stop":396.706,"duration":4.12},{"text":"When the first five years was over, which occurred in 1953, and negotiated from 1953 to 1954 and adopted the definitive terms, in the renegotiation of the lease rather than raise their -- lower their rent because they were having a burden of a tax or speculate on that because of the tax, it was agreed that the United States would -- by contract the United States assumed full burden of this tax in order to get the lease terms as satisfactory to the United States as they were.","start":396.706,"stop":427.717,"duration":31.01}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"That wasn't a legal obligation, that is just the --","start":427.717,"stop":430.092,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":430.092,"stop":430.828,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"They just decided to do that, didn't they?","start":430.828,"stop":433.421,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":433.421,"stop":434.035,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"So we can't proceed here on the theory that if we decide this case against the government that we are throwing the burden on the government as a matter of law.","start":434.035,"stop":442.711,"duration":8.68}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Not as matter of law, no, except in this case there was a contract outstanding with the United States (Inaudible), it will pay the tax under the period of the lease, I thought Your Honor would like to note, this was the -- I assume you would, that this is the fact situation here and as a practical matter if a lease that the lessee of property must pay a tax, the amount that is paid for the lease is substantially than the lessee need not pay a tax.","start":442.711,"stop":467.197,"duration":24.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What you're saying really, is that what you are saying, the question therefore comes down whether when the government does make a contract like that, and it is empowered to make such a contract I take it, it lifts the tax burden from everybody?","start":467.197,"stop":485.788,"duration":18.59}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"No I am not to saying that the fact that the United States is paying this tax means this is the tax upon the United States.","start":485.788,"stop":491.443,"duration":5.65}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I am not saying that either, that was my question.","start":491.443,"stop":496.223,"duration":4.78},{"text":"On the basis of such a contract which the government is empowered to make, when it chooses to make it, it creates a situation whereby immunity results.","start":496.223,"stop":507.69,"duration":11.47}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"By contract Borg-Warner does not have to pay this tax, the burden is passed on to the United States.","start":507.69,"stop":512.441,"duration":4.75}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Now are those the same thing, is this an answer to what Justice Frankfurter --","start":512.441,"stop":518.207,"duration":5.77}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"If I understood your question correctly Mr. Justice Frankfurter.","start":518.207,"stop":520.778,"duration":2.57}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well let me put my question again because it is important.","start":520.778,"stop":525.031,"duration":4.25},{"text":"Of course the government can give (Inaudible) if it wants to, that's a totally different -- that isn't your proposition here that it came (Inaudible).","start":525.031,"stop":533.102,"duration":8.07},{"text":"Your proposition is that when this contract, when this lease was made, which the government was free to make or not free to make, necessarily as a matter of law, immunity results from it, because of the relation of the arrangement to the United Sates.","start":533.102,"stop":550.443,"duration":17.34},{"text":"Is that right?","start":550.443,"stop":551.133,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's see if I stated -- the United Sates owned this plant.","start":551.133,"stop":554.924,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Whatever -- (Inaudible)","start":554.924,"stop":556.184,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"No there was no interest in anyone else except the United States and the naval reserve plant in Detroit.","start":556.184,"stop":561.931,"duration":5.75},{"text":"It was every interest within the United States.","start":561.931,"stop":564.242,"duration":2.31},{"text":"At that point the United States leased out to Borg-Warner, let them use the plant.","start":564.242,"stop":570.719,"duration":6.48},{"text":"The contention of Michigan is they may now impose a tax on that privilege of using the government plant, the tax exempt plant.","start":570.719,"stop":579.265,"duration":8.55},{"text":"That -- we contend that this tax is a substantive tax on the plant and that it is not permitted either under the implied immunity or under congressional action in this field.","start":579.265,"stop":588.971,"duration":9.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Which means that if the government -- if the contract -- if the lease didn't provide or if there wasn't a statute which specifically authorized Michigan to impose such a tax, it couldn't.","start":588.971,"stop":601.374,"duration":12.4}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right and I believe the situation would be exactly the same if Borg-Warner were required to pay the tax by the contract.","start":601.374,"stop":608.733,"duration":7.36},{"text":"We are not contending that that makes any difference in the imposition of the tax.","start":608.733,"stop":612.928,"duration":4.2}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I gather in the -- practical effect is that if this tax has to be paid by someone, the lessee is not going to pay as much rent as otherwise United States could get him to pay.","start":612.928,"stop":622.686,"duration":9.76}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, the -- that's correct, Your Honor.","start":622.686,"stop":625.168,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's all there is to it, this conversation we have been having back and forth.","start":625.168,"stop":630.161,"duration":4.99}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes Your Honor I believe that that the -- whether by contract or indirectly the burden of such arrangement is going to be reflected in United States, here it's reflected directly.","start":630.161,"stop":641.323,"duration":11.16},{"text":"The Continental --","start":641.323,"stop":642.1,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) the government chooses – it confers such a benefit upon the lessee, he has the right too, Constitutional right.","start":642.1,"stop":650.829,"duration":8.73}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree -- I accept that Your Honor.","start":650.829,"stop":653.017,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well aren't there other considerations Mr. Fisher besides the rent that these lessees will pay which determines whether or not the government will lease to a given lessee?","start":653.017,"stop":665.771,"duration":12.75}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"There are number of considerations and this is one.","start":665.771,"stop":668.655,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But this is not – this is -- this doesn't optimize that?","start":668.655,"stop":671.715,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Well the tax on the Continental property is around $900,000.","start":671.715,"stop":676.887,"duration":5.17}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I am not thinking of that.","start":676.887,"stop":677.028,"duration":0.14},{"text":"I mean the choice of a lessee for one of these government owned arsenals or whatever they maybe is dictated by considerations that is more important than the --","start":677.028,"stop":688.891,"duration":11.86}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Than the local taxes.","start":688.891,"stop":689.425,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Problem of tax.","start":689.425,"stop":690.506,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe that's true Your Honor.","start":690.506,"stop":691.593,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Or the amount of the rent that the lessee will pay.","start":691.593,"stop":694.218,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"The rent sometimes becomes significant, fairly substantial item.","start":694.218,"stop":698.016,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Maybe a substantial item but in the choice of lessee is it a significant consideration?","start":698.016,"stop":701.633,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"No I don't believe it, I do not.","start":701.633,"stop":705.041,"duration":3.41},{"text":"The critical difference between the Continental case in Muskegon and the Borg-Warner case is that Continental has no lease.","start":705.041,"stop":712.508,"duration":7.47},{"text":"Continental is there under a facilities procurement type contract, which we provide the complete plant.","start":712.508,"stop":719.11,"duration":6.6},{"text":"Continental makes defense goods in that plant for the United States.","start":719.11,"stop":725.031,"duration":5.92},{"text":"It is not, its occupancy is not under -- not governed by the Military Leasing Act of 1947.","start":725.031,"stop":731.521,"duration":6.49},{"text":"Everything it manufactures in the plant is for the United States.","start":731.521,"stop":735.127,"duration":3.61},{"text":"It is doing the government's business on the government's property for a contract price, making goods.","start":735.127,"stop":740.67,"duration":5.54},{"text":"In that cost basis, it cannot reflect any element of cost that comes from the plant or the equipment supplied by the government.","start":740.67,"stop":749.287,"duration":8.62},{"text":"Here again the property was valued precisely as it would have been, as the property was owned in fee simple occupied by Continental Motors.","start":749.287,"stop":757.62,"duration":8.33},{"text":"The rates for real property taxes in Muskegon took into account the assessment on this and determined tax rate would be.","start":757.62,"stop":765.135,"duration":7.51},{"text":"It was treated as a real property tax.","start":765.135,"stop":768.279,"duration":3.14},{"text":"In the computation of the tax, the tax -- it was carried on the same real property tax roll.","start":768.279,"stop":774.244,"duration":5.97},{"text":"The tax bill sent out was identical to that sent to real property owners.","start":774.244,"stop":779.115,"duration":4.87},{"text":"Continental did not pay the tax.","start":779.115,"stop":781.848,"duration":2.73},{"text":"A suit was brought by the township of Muskegon, the county of Muskegon and the local school district.","start":781.848,"stop":788.478,"duration":6.63},{"text":"United States intervened as the party defendant.","start":788.478,"stop":791.146,"duration":2.67},{"text":"Both the County Court and the Supreme Court of Michigan entered judgment for the municipal corporations.","start":791.146,"stop":805.448,"duration":14.3},{"text":"The government's position is very clear.","start":805.448,"stop":808.477,"duration":3.03},{"text":"The Michigan's Act 189 impinges upon the implied immunity of United States property and state taxation, which exists in the absence of Congressional acts in the field.","start":808.477,"stop":818.926,"duration":10.45},{"text":"Both because it is a -- in substance purpose and affects a tax on the real property, the value of the real property and because it is designed as compensatory or retaliatory tax directed solely at tax exempt property.","start":818.926,"stop":835.901,"duration":16.97},{"text":"We think under the implied immunity it is there on both of too grounds.","start":835.901,"stop":838.841,"duration":2.94},{"text":"Our second argument, it stems from the fact that Congress has legislated in this field.","start":838.841,"stop":844.189,"duration":5.35},{"text":"The Military Leasing Act which specifically applies to Borg-Warner plant provides that the lessee's interest shall be made subject to taxation.","start":844.189,"stop":852.819,"duration":8.63},{"text":"The legislative history of that act considered by this Court in the (Inaudible) case makes clear that Congress intended to know more in the value of the leasehold interest through the subject of tax for leases made under the military --","start":852.819,"stop":865.547,"duration":12.73}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I appreciate the choices that advocate is making their argument but I wonder why you, why you say your second argument is the statute, because if the statute is pretty clear --","start":865.547,"stop":877.895,"duration":12.35}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"The statute does not --","start":877.895,"stop":879.495,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it takes care of all my worries.","start":879.495,"stop":881.3,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Frankfurter the statute by it terms does not apply to the Continental Plant.","start":881.3,"stop":886.298,"duration":5},{"text":"The -- there they will have no lease whatsoever.","start":886.298,"stop":889.654,"duration":3.36},{"text":"There it's a procurement contract under procurement authority of the United States that makes available the plant to them and it's tamable at will as soon as they stop making supply for the United States, as soon as United States which has the option to cancel that contract, they are out, they can be put out the next day.","start":889.654,"stop":909.167,"duration":19.51},{"text":"And this is why I direct my argument first that the implied immunity which we believe covers both cases very clearly, and secondly the legislation which specifically applied in one case in which we think reflect a policy that it's applicable to the second case.","start":909.167,"stop":924.025,"duration":14.86}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's a good answer.","start":924.025,"stop":927.042,"duration":3.02}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"This tax is in substance a tax on property of the United States.","start":927.042,"stop":932.716,"duration":5.67},{"text":"The act which appears in our brief for appellants on page 29 is entitled “An act to provide for the taxation of lessees and users of tax exempt property.”","start":932.716,"stop":945.988,"duration":13.27},{"text":"And any real property, which for any reason is exempt from taxation is leased et cetera are made available and used by private individual or corporation, in connection with the business conducted for property, then they have exception which is unimportant then it says ‘shall be subject.'","start":945.988,"stop":965.129,"duration":19.14},{"text":"Unfortunately in the drafting of this legislative history of this act the predicate to ‘shall be subject' was left out.","start":965.129,"stop":971.042,"duration":5.91},{"text":"The Supreme Court of Michigan has told us what should be there and it should -- you should read as inserted in there the lessee or user of such property shall be subject to taxation in the same amount and to the same extent as though the lessee or user or the owner of such property.","start":971.042,"stop":990.759,"duration":19.72},{"text":"And the second section provides with or -- I should go on provide explicitly before going shall not apply to federal property for which payments are made in lieu of taxes in amounts equivalent to taxes, which might otherwise be lawfully assessed.","start":990.759,"stop":1007.665,"duration":16.91},{"text":"Section two provide the taxes to be assessed with such lessees and users and collect in the same manner as the real estate taxes except they shall not become a lien on the property.","start":1007.665,"stop":1022.925,"duration":15.26}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you mind telling, if you don't mind what spell that out concretely for which payments are made in lieu of taxes, how are the payments made to --","start":1022.925,"stop":1030.604,"duration":7.68}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Congress has in a large number of cases specifically authorized legislation making payments in lieu of taxes.","start":1030.604,"stop":1038.455,"duration":7.85},{"text":"As to this particular plant in Continental, Congress has authorized payments in lieu of taxes since this case started, there's legislation referred to in both decrees delaying with it.","start":1038.455,"stop":1048.016,"duration":9.56}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Congress just doesn't pay the taxes?","start":1048.016,"stop":1049.884,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Congress says we will make payments in lieu of taxes and they will be worked out in the following fashion.","start":1049.884,"stop":1054.856,"duration":4.97},{"text":"This -- the statute which I referred, public law 388, only applied to plants that were taken from the RFC to United States or to some branch of United States which would make it tax exempt.","start":1054.856,"stop":1070.059,"duration":15.2},{"text":"The Continental plant now operated by Continental in Muskegon was held by the RFC.","start":1070.059,"stop":1076.148,"duration":6.09},{"text":"It was taxable.","start":1076.148,"stop":1077.171,"duration":1.02},{"text":"They were receiving tax payments from it.","start":1077.171,"stop":1080.176,"duration":3},{"text":"It was conveyed in liquidation of the RFC was conveyed to the United States, just remove it from the tax rolls, one year later Congress got around and said to make payments in lieu of taxes while considering --","start":1080.176,"stop":1089.852,"duration":9.68}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"These are -- these are ad hoc measures, my brother Burton reminds of that in the housing act, there's a general provision --","start":1089.852,"stop":1096.706,"duration":6.85}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"We have in our reply brief we have listed legislation effect on various types of payments in the appendix, showing all existing legislation as of this tax day, various types of payments which Congress was authorizing.","start":1096.706,"stop":1108.432,"duration":11.73}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you draw any, do you get any comfort out of those specific enactment?","start":1108.432,"stop":1113.968,"duration":5.54}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"I certainly do Your Honor, I believe that this is a field in which Congress has repeatedly legislated, dealt with the very plant here involved that is provided for payment for education, the school district which is here as a plaintiff has received payments as federal aid to impacted area that is calculated by the number of children of parents working in the plant receive a certain percentage of aid not in the year in question, but the years before and years of the annual reports of the Commissioner of Education indicate.","start":1113.968,"stop":1146.891,"duration":32.92},{"text":"This tax is a, the assessment procedure the computation of the tax--","start":1146.891,"stop":1150.639,"duration":3.75}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Where does that leaves you to by comparison with this case?","start":1150.639,"stop":1156.886,"duration":6.25},{"text":"You say you take a lot of comfort out of them doing that in a lot of cases now where do you get your comfort in the fact that it hasn't been done in these other cases?","start":1156.886,"stop":1165.583,"duration":8.7}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"That Congress has the authority where it sees fit to extend the immunity to contractors as this Court held in Carson against Roane-Anderson where contractors with the Atomic Energy Commission are made exempt from use tax in Tennessee because of -- by Congress' statute said so and necessary and proper clause of authorized functions.","start":1165.583,"stop":1191.613,"duration":26.03},{"text":"Congress can waive the tax.","start":1191.613,"stop":1194.597,"duration":2.98},{"text":"Congress has for a hundred years and particularly in the last 10 years given extreme consideration to this particular problem, assuming that defense plants owned by United States, the value of those plants cannot be taxed.","start":1194.597,"stop":1208.484,"duration":13.89},{"text":"They have -- it's a very difficult problem in which it's hard to appraise the equities.","start":1208.484,"stop":1213.703,"duration":5.22},{"text":"Sometimes the plant is setup in nowhere a community goes around it, which grew its benefit from the plant, they then say we want to tax the whole atomic energy installation here, now we have village, we're assessing the tax, we think we ought to collect revenue.","start":1213.703,"stop":1227.215,"duration":13.51},{"text":"That case is quite different than the case here in Muskegon where there was a plant on tax rolls which comprised half the school district here involved, assessed value or something of that kind, which was taken off the rolls, in that case Congress has legislated providing that payments in lieu of taxes shall be made to the Continental Motors Corporations, it was included in the list of plants covered by this provision and until 1959 and they now have other legislation pending and in the works trying to deal with the problem in a broader way.","start":1227.215,"stop":1257.721,"duration":30.51}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Problem as a general problem or specific, ad hoc?","start":1257.721,"stop":1261.607,"duration":3.89}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"They are trying to find legislation dealing with them in a general way, the answer that most bills come to is you have to have some administrative discretion to decide on ad hoc cases --","start":1261.607,"stop":1272.228,"duration":10.62}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What if they are 100 years Mr. Fisher, I'm not greatly impressed by that century because up to the Dravo decision, as Justice Roberts pointed in his dissent Alleghany, you had the whole atmosphere, the whole momentum of the decisions of this Court.","start":1272.228,"stop":1290.203,"duration":17.97},{"text":"It was very different from happened after Dravo, but the whole thing shifted from a, if I may respectfully say to rather abstract discussion of federal state relations to the concreteness of the Dravo and even the concreteness of Alleghany, isn't that true?","start":1290.203,"stop":1309.452,"duration":19.25}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"That is -- I agree Your Honor and we have in the back of our reply brief, we have called attention to the particular consideration which Congress has given this in the last five Congresses.","start":1309.452,"stop":1318.958,"duration":9.51},{"text":"Over 100 bills were introduced on it.","start":1318.958,"stop":1321.02,"duration":2.06},{"text":"There are elaborate reports considering payments in lieu of taxes, profit sharing, cost sharing, revenue sharing, devices of every kind.","start":1321.02,"stop":1330.725,"duration":9.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Are there many -- are there many such bills in lieu of bills?","start":1330.725,"stop":1334.487,"duration":3.76}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes Your Honor there are.","start":1334.487,"stop":1335.242,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well maybe -- would you think it was fantastic for me to draw a contrary inference from yours to say that, that shows that on the whole maybe Congress going about its business the way it does case by case, maybe Congress thereby indicated the immunity is not wisely left to the government, that this Court should reconsider the general problem.","start":1335.242,"stop":1357.025,"duration":21.78}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"I think Your Honor if you look at the reports which went with these bills for the in lieu payments that are interim nature that were adopted, you will see that was not the conclusion which was motivating --","start":1357.025,"stop":1365.454,"duration":8.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean there that the Congress has shown a commendable respect for the decisions of this Court.","start":1365.454,"stop":1369.955,"duration":4.5}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah I believe [Laughter].","start":1369.955,"stop":1372.231,"duration":2.28},{"text":"If Your Honor if I may say, the Congress in respect for this decisions of this Court recognized that it has the power to grant or waive tax immunity in this field.","start":1372.231,"stop":1381.416,"duration":9.18}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well Mr. Fisher isn't there a lot of difference between the kind of in lieu taxes that the situations in which the government pays in lieu taxes by congressional enactment say under the Lanham Act or under the Taylor Grazing Act or under the Housing Act and things of that kind where there would be an exemption and where they want to take care of the local governments because they know the necessities of local government where they are furnishing police protection and fire protection, schools and highways and things of that kind for these great industries, isn't that one thing and isn't it quite another thing when you get a situation of this kind and isn't it just as normal to believe that Congress thought that the lessees in cases of this kind were subject to local taxes?","start":1381.416,"stop":1445.031,"duration":63.62},{"text":"Is there anything in the legislative history to show that Congress thought that lessees of this kind are exempt and should be exempt because of the government exemption?","start":1445.031,"stop":1454.981,"duration":9.95}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes Your Honor there is very clear legislative history establishing that beyond for a venture.","start":1454.981,"stop":1460.44,"duration":5.46},{"text":"Printed in Appendix A to our reply brief is the discussion in the Senate, first in the House, this is in the Senate Committee, Appendix A considering the Military Leasing Act at 1947.","start":1460.44,"stop":1472.159,"duration":11.72},{"text":"We have reprinted the entire committee colloquy on this point for the use of the courts that I will not be -- might I fear taken out of context, it's fairly -- there are ten pages of discussion.","start":1472.159,"stop":1482.401,"duration":10.24},{"text":"This first statement which is the first time they refer to this problem is Senator Byrd --","start":1482.401,"stop":1487.154,"duration":4.75}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What page?","start":1487.154,"stop":1487.939,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"On page 26 of my reply brief in 26, 37 and 38.","start":1487.939,"stop":1494.31,"duration":6.37},{"text":"On page 26, Senator Byrd, “I'd like to ask about Section 6 in regard to taxation.","start":1494.31,"stop":1499.692,"duration":5.38},{"text":"Does this mean that if this property is taxed by the state and local governments it would have to be by an act of Congress?”","start":1499.692,"stop":1505.904,"duration":6.21},{"text":"Mr. Kenney, “It would sir” and it goes on and on and Mr. -- Senator Byrd, “This is no authorization.”","start":1505.904,"stop":1511.97,"duration":6.07}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Who was Mr. Kenney?","start":1511.97,"stop":1513.57,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"He was Assistant Secretory of the Navy.","start":1513.57,"stop":1515.976,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"John Kenney?","start":1515.976,"stop":1517.496,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah John Kenney who was testifying before the administration in presenting the bill.","start":1517.496,"stop":1522.716,"duration":5.22},{"text":"Senate -- to page 27 --","start":1522.716,"stop":1524.29,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What does that answer means, if would, that's his understanding of the law?","start":1524.29,"stop":1528.456,"duration":4.17}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"And if I may carry Your Honors along with me through this discussion of Senate Committee, Mr. Kenney said at the bottom of page 27, “Well we do under this bill in no way increases or decreases the amount of taxes to which these properties maybe subject to,” pointing out they were in the United States and were not taxable at that time.","start":1528.456,"stop":1548.174,"duration":19.72},{"text":"Senator Baldwin on page 29 of our brief, middle, lower middle of the page, posed, “What would you think about language providing that property leased to private persons, corporate or individuals pursuant to this provisions of this Act shall be subject to state and local taxation in accordance with such state and tax law, would that answer your question” and then Mr. Royale on page 30 --","start":1548.174,"stop":1573.059,"duration":24.88}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's with that page 26 for a moment, right after the question and answer you read, Senator Byrd said, “Of course there is a question involved there of taking these plants and leasing them to private companies and the private companies making a profit.”","start":1573.059,"stop":1592.606,"duration":19.55},{"text":"It is a question of whether or not they should not pay taxes to the local and state governments, very much what we have here.","start":1592.606,"stop":1600.518,"duration":7.91}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, both --","start":1600.518,"stop":1601.245,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"And then Mr. Kenney said, “My own feeling is Senator that taxes should be paid on property that is used for that purpose.”","start":1601.245,"stop":1609.928,"duration":8.68},{"text":"The federal government in making its terms of lease should agree with the local authorities that they will pay the amount of taxes that would have otherwise accrued.","start":1609.928,"stop":1619.747,"duration":9.82}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"In the next colloquy --","start":1619.747,"stop":1621.205,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) your position?","start":1621.205,"stop":1622.136,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes it does Your Honor.","start":1622.136,"stop":1623.393,"duration":1.26},{"text":"Both of them thought it to be desirable and both of them thought this would not impossible without further legislation.","start":1623.393,"stop":1629.043,"duration":5.65},{"text":"They decided not to put that legislation in this Act, the next colloquy, the next two sentences, Senator Byrd says, “Can you do that legally if the title is vested in the government itself.”","start":1629.043,"stop":1638.791,"duration":9.75},{"text":"Mr. Kenny, “You can do it only if Congress so authorizes.”","start":1638.791,"stop":1641.771,"duration":2.98}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's his view of the law.","start":1641.771,"stop":1643.16,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"That is true.","start":1643.16,"stop":1646.126,"duration":2.97},{"text":"The drafting of the sentence which appears at the first sentence of Section 6 of the Military Leasing Act, took place in the committee in the open hearings, pages 35 and 36 of our brief, and there were some suggestion that there is no reason to do this because they can do it already.","start":1646.126,"stop":1662.171,"duration":16.05},{"text":"Senator Tydings on page 35, “As a matter of fact if the government leases to corporation AB a plant for a period of five years without us doing anything about it, they would be taxable by each community of America, the tax of leasehold property, so why put anything in?”","start":1662.171,"stop":1676.524,"duration":14.35},{"text":"Mr. Kenney, “I do not think you should anything in this bill.”","start":1676.524,"stop":1680.31,"duration":3.79},{"text":"Senator Tydings, so forth, they then went on and decided that there ought to be something added to that, and --","start":1680.31,"stop":1687.515,"duration":7.21}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Who said that?","start":1687.515,"stop":1690.001,"duration":2.49}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Senator Tydings, near the top of page 36 on my brief.","start":1690.001,"stop":1694.791,"duration":4.79},{"text":"Senator Hill, “Something ought to going on there,” as it is now which you have the second sentence of Section 6 was all he had.","start":1694.791,"stop":1702.183,"duration":7.39},{"text":"All you do is say in the event, the state does come along and tax one of these lessees you renegotiate the contract and so forth and Mr. Royale, “We would have to do that, they have to know the basis on which they lease it.”","start":1702.183,"stop":1715.874,"duration":13.69},{"text":"Explaining in the absence of this (Inaudible) he would insist on a larger rental and it's the Chairman, “Have you got the wording in shape, now (Inaudible)?","start":1715.874,"stop":1725.35,"duration":9.48},{"text":"This does not read very smoothly,” Senator Tydings, “How would it be to say that the lessee's interest in property maybe subject to tax by a local authority.”","start":1725.35,"stop":1733.067,"duration":7.72},{"text":"Mr. Kenny, “Any interest of the lessee created pursuant to provisions of this Act, maybe subject to local taxation.”","start":1733.067,"stop":1738.624,"duration":5.56},{"text":"Chairman, “Read off in full Mr. Secretary.”","start":1738.624,"stop":1740.878,"duration":2.25},{"text":"Mr. Royale reading, the lessee's interest made or created pursuant to the provisions of this Act shall be made subject to state or local taxation.","start":1740.878,"stop":1748.924,"duration":8.05},{"text":"In the face of the fact they were told they could not tax anymore than the lessee's interest under existing law which could impose a lease or attack on the valuable lease hold, the fact that the bills were then pending in Congress dealing with the general problem, we conclude that for a property under the Military Leasing Act you cannot tax more than the value of the leasehold interest, that is not was what was assessed here.","start":1748.924,"stop":1774.194,"duration":25.27}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Fisher I'd like to pursue a question I put to you earlier.","start":1774.194,"stop":1780.823,"duration":6.63},{"text":"In as much as these immunizations are implied, as you indicate, we haven't got a case here where the Congress of the United States affirmatively says that they shall not tax.","start":1780.823,"stop":1793.683,"duration":12.86},{"text":"That may raise a question as to whether, to what extent Congress of the United States can withdraw from the taxing power of a state, power that it otherwise enjoys, but assume as I will, because I'm ready to -- that legislation, whatever maybe the answer, argumentatively, congressional explicit legislation could withdraw any time in even remote interest of the United States from the taxing power of the state, we haven't got that situation, we got the reverse situation.","start":1793.683,"stop":1826.182,"duration":32.5},{"text":"We've got immunity derived impliedly from the relation between state and federal government that's correct, isn't it?","start":1826.182,"stop":1833.006,"duration":6.82},{"text":"That's the basis of this, is that correct?","start":1833.006,"stop":1836.307,"duration":3.3}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the legislation -- I might put a little more legislative history than you would on it --","start":1836.307,"stop":1841.055,"duration":4.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not talking about legislative history --","start":1841.055,"stop":1842.805,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"The facts are you are right.","start":1842.805,"stop":1843.848,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1843.848,"stop":1844.818,"duration":0.97},{"text":"Though that -- now, since the history of this problem is a history of judicial implications from state, federal relations and one can be as you indicated a little while ago in agreement, I suppose one can't disagree, that Dravo, what I call Dravo, the whole series of Dravo decisions made a considerable shift to the attitude of this Court.","start":1844.818,"stop":1871.797,"duration":26.98}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"There's no doubt about","start":1871.797,"stop":1873.001,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"A considerable shift, or important shift, a far reaching shift, took it out of more or less mechanical or generalized category and wanted to find some real burden, some real incursion, some real hampering or embarrassment, financial or otherwise to the activities of the federal government, you still agree with me, don't you?","start":1873.001,"stop":1897.71,"duration":24.71}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"If you put financial in there, I agree.","start":1897.71,"stop":1899.713,"duration":2},{"text":"I think that any tax burden is only a financial burden, United States can't by payments avoid any other consequences of taxation.","start":1899.713,"stop":1907.593,"duration":7.88}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But this is not such a Dravo.","start":1907.593,"stop":1909.689,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"No I know taxes that -- financial burden is no enough, so I don't --","start":1909.689,"stop":1912.683,"duration":2.99}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Dravo destroys the notion that merely the fact that the Secretary of the Treasury has to figure out a few extra dollars or many, many dollars, isn't enough to withdraw -- to give immunity that is correct.","start":1912.683,"stop":1924.945,"duration":12.26}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":1924.945,"stop":1926.173,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, after this long speech what I like to put to you is this, this Court has said again and again that we may draw a jural premise from legislation, particularly a series of enactments and if we have in this domain a series of ad hoc provisions and the general attitude on the part of Congress whereby they feel urged or they feel a sense of injustice or they feel unfairness to the state more particular to continue to this immunity, why doesn't that afford us a spring board for working this thing out judiciously so as to carry on the Dravo premise, that's my problem here.","start":1926.173,"stop":1969.237,"duration":43.06}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"The every item of legislation Your Honor that has been adopted here by Congress dealing with this problem, reflects the immensity and difficulty of drawing a line between where the equities falls, where a town benefits enormously from a government plan and where it is hurt.","start":1969.237,"stop":1990.122,"duration":20.88},{"text":"Where if as if in the Borg-Warner case there is a lot of government property leased to Borg-Warner for storage against crisis, since it's in the lease property Borg-Warner has to look after it for us.","start":1990.122,"stop":2004.905,"duration":14.78},{"text":"There would been no equity in charging Borg-Warner a tax on that property whereas the national forests, private parties are allowed to use the national forests, to cut some timber off it.","start":2004.905,"stop":2017.075,"duration":12.17},{"text":"We have a sharing arrangement that's been worked out, in which the state gets 25% I believe of the proceeds of such sales.","start":2017.075,"stop":2023.625,"duration":6.55},{"text":"If the state can also tax a party for the privilege of using the national forest, measured by the value of the national forest, the situation is quite different.","start":2023.625,"stop":2032.799,"duration":9.17},{"text":"I believe -- the reason that I think this is -- legislation indicates this is not an area for judicial reconstruction, is any decision of this Court, dealing with this problem would merely add one unexpected complicating feature to a problem with which Congress has the power to deal, is dealing and would have to deal even more comprehensively.","start":2032.799,"stop":2057.324,"duration":24.53},{"text":"The in-lieu payments are not just for defense plants.","start":2057.324,"stop":2060.746,"duration":3.42},{"text":"The in-lieu payments that authorize interim bill and Public Law 388, are for plants which by virtue of the transfer from RFC were taken off tax rolls.","start":2060.746,"stop":2071.94,"duration":11.19},{"text":"Congress recognized a quite different situation where they put a defense plant out in nowhere and a small community has grown around it in and which proposing a tax burden on the value of the entire plant for the benefit of the small community which may or may not be providing services to the plant, is not the way to deal with the problem.","start":2071.94,"stop":2093.056,"duration":21.12},{"text":"You should hold that the state may not tax the property, it may tax the privilege of using the property measured by the property.","start":2093.056,"stop":2100.446,"duration":7.39},{"text":"You would be making this problem one of form not of substance.","start":2100.446,"stop":2104.082,"duration":3.64},{"text":"If you continue to say that government property is immune from taxation directly, but if a state changes ten words, they don't change their administrative machinery, they cause a tax on the privilege of using tax exempt property.","start":2104.082,"stop":2118.45,"duration":14.37},{"text":"And by doing that, you say, oh a state can, that's all right oh this is a tax on a privilege, this is not a tax on the property, it's just measured by the property.","start":2118.45,"stop":2127.522,"duration":9.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) a vast amount of tax law is based just on that distinction?","start":2127.522,"stop":2131.495,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"And I believe that this fails to meet that, this is not a privilege, the privilege using tax exemption property is not a privilege like being a store of gasoline or being a butcher or a baker or a candle stick maker.","start":2131.495,"stop":2144.513,"duration":13.02},{"text":"The privilege of using federal property is one which the United States has exclusive and decided who it is going to lease this property.","start":2144.513,"stop":2151.187,"duration":6.67},{"text":"This is more like Leslie Miller and Arkansas which you had last year, where the privilege of dealing with the government is something which we confer by our lease.","start":2151.187,"stop":2161.366,"duration":10.18},{"text":"This is a state, this is not a general right which the state can say, oh this is kind of doing business cause, using tax exempt property.","start":2161.366,"stop":2171.374,"duration":10.01},{"text":"First place it is a directed as being taxing it because it's not taxable and we think than under the Miller and Milwaukee and Macallen against Massachusetts, two decision of this Court which where the Justice Holmes in the Milwaukee case said if the abound purpose or self evident operation of a statute is to follow the bonds of the United States and to make up for its inability to reach them directly, by indirectly achieving the same result, the statute must fail, even if but for its purpose or special operations it would be perfectly good.","start":2171.374,"stop":2212.378,"duration":41},{"text":"In both that case and the Massachusetts case taxes were found, they looked through the language to find the tax was really directed at tax exempt interest, tax exempt property and both were held invalid for that reason.","start":2212.378,"stop":2225.693,"duration":13.32}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"As against that other cases and the tax measures in which state taxes are more heavily fall on -- company theretofore are immune from taxation, because the government owned it.","start":2225.693,"stop":2242.372,"duration":16.68},{"text":"In other words, if an estate has a lot of bonds, they were bonds which as such are immune, you can more heavily impose on a state tax on an estate that include, because of the immunity they have enjoyed the life time of the (Inaudible) and when you say the government, of course the government grants the privilege, but the fellow who gets it, gets something that some other people don't get.","start":2242.372,"stop":2266.066,"duration":23.69}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"And we submit and we agree, they can tax the value of what he gets.","start":2266.066,"stop":2270.967,"duration":4.9},{"text":"They can say we are taxing, and I think you could have a tax on the lessee's tax exempt property measured by the value of the interest which the lessee has.","start":2270.967,"stop":2280.176,"duration":9.21},{"text":"I think the Military Leasing Act saying that lessee's interest is taxable is good, I think its declaratory of the implied immunity that exists in assets of that legislation, as Congress plainly saw.","start":2280.176,"stop":2292.154,"duration":11.98},{"text":"I believe that the Borg-Warner case, where Borg-Warner has a 20-year – in effect a 20-year lease subject to five years installments, they now have, I don't know 12 years still to run, that's 11 years.","start":2292.154,"stop":2304.947,"duration":12.79},{"text":"Detroit could tax the same way you would in a condemnation case, a recognized judicial concept of the lessee's interest, the leasehold interest he has certain value and you can tax it.","start":2304.947,"stop":2315.47,"duration":10.52},{"text":"We think the implied immunity of the legislation you can tax it, but if you say that because a man is using government property for the government's business as is being done in the Continental plan, you can tax him for the privilege of using that because he has something of value.","start":2315.47,"stop":2333.356,"duration":17.89},{"text":"I believe you have a hard time distinguishing taxing Secretary McElroy for the privilege of using the Pentagon measured by the value of the Pentagon.","start":2333.356,"stop":2341.033,"duration":7.68},{"text":"Continental is making government equipment in a government plant, excuse me Your Honor.","start":2341.033,"stop":2344.737,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"You say that Congress couldn't take away that right as to lessee on the value of his lease?","start":2344.737,"stop":2350.912,"duration":6.17}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I believe Congress could take away that right --","start":2350.912,"stop":2353.562,"duration":2.65}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"They could take that away also --","start":2353.562,"stop":2354.562,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe under the case which this Court held recently in the connection with Atomic and Carson against Roane-Anderson in 342 U.S.","start":2354.562,"stop":2362.845,"duration":8.28},{"text":"It specifically held that Congress could take -- make contractors with the Atomic Energy Commission, immune from use taxes on goods which they brought into the state, and this Court held that's what the construction of the statute was and that it was valid.","start":2362.845,"stop":2376.612,"duration":13.77},{"text":"So I believe clearly in the necessary and proper powers carrying on legislative function, if we have a plant such as Borg-Warner, a large portion of it merely storing defense equipment, we may want to get a lessee in there free, to use part of the plant in exchange for keeping up our portion of the plant and I think if we couldn't do that about having a large tax burden, additional imposed, Congress can say no it's in connection with this function, the lessee is not, he just cannot be taxed.","start":2376.612,"stop":2407.773,"duration":31.16}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You say, you say there is a real disturb -- it will be disturbing for a judicial pronouncement that the privilege of having a leasehold from the government is taxable, isn't that true, do you think that will be a --","start":2407.773,"stop":2423.921,"duration":16.15}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it will be disturbing --","start":2423.921,"stop":2425.65,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"A crude way for the judiciary to enter into the problem.","start":2425.65,"stop":2428.554,"duration":2.9}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"If I may expand on that Your Honor, I think that will be disturbing if you indicated they could tax that privilege measured not by the value of the privilege but by the value of the tax exempt property.","start":2428.554,"stop":2441.361,"duration":12.81},{"text":"Whereas I think that here where a tax is special discriminatorily if I may say directed at tax exempt property, both state tax exempt to be sure and federal tax exempt, but the thrust of it is that federal -- that was true in both the Milwaukee and the Massachusetts cases, there were state taxes on property included and the court still not found a thing discriminatorily directed impact of the federal property.","start":2441.361,"stop":2464.148,"duration":22.79}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But whenever you have a formula to try to keep one particular class of property from escaping, I suppose you could call that a discriminatory -- that discriminatory, but do you have the same sense?","start":2464.148,"stop":2476.841,"duration":12.69}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"I very -- to be sure to some extent to which form is important and if the statute were more artfully drawn, you might have more difficulty with it and it might accomplish almost the same result, but I believe that it is plain on its face that this is a real, they do nothing, they don't setup new machinery, they don't setup different evaluation procedures, part of the real property tax system of Michigan, each community in Muskegon is carried under real property tax rolls, they send out real property tax bills.","start":2476.841,"stop":2511.894,"duration":35.05},{"text":"They say Act 189 has the authority for taxing.","start":2511.894,"stop":2516.279,"duration":4.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Do they do it as to other leaseholds?","start":2516.279,"stop":2520.094,"duration":3.82}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"There were four Detroit cases --","start":2520.094,"stop":2521.602,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I am not taking about government leaseholds.","start":2521.602,"stop":2525.533,"duration":3.93}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"The Detroit tax record is in the record here, show that under Act 189 there were four properties that were taxed under 189 in Detroit.","start":2525.533,"stop":2534.887,"duration":9.35},{"text":"There was testimony these were either federal or held by corporation exempt under Michigan state law.","start":2534.887,"stop":2543.227,"duration":8.34},{"text":"It's not clear which, which if any.","start":2543.227,"stop":2545.472,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well is there any discrimination or unfair discrimination in a city trying to see whether a manufacturer who comes into the community and who demands fire protection, police protection and all the other services of the city shall not escape taxation?","start":2545.472,"stop":2571.762,"duration":26.29},{"text":"And let's just take -- let's just take some particular --","start":2571.762,"stop":2575.408,"duration":3.65}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"To case here --","start":2575.408,"stop":2576.981,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I can recall one were the city of 35,000 people, overnight the government brought a contractor in there to build a shipyard, 65,000 people came there to work in the period of a –in a period of year-and-a-half.","start":2576.981,"stop":2594.661,"duration":17.68},{"text":"Schools, highways, housing, hospitals everything that community had to spend money for, for all those people, is there any -- is there anything wrong in the city trying to, to prevent an operator of that kind from paying taxes that will enable it to operate the city government on a somewhat fair basis with other citizens of the community?","start":2594.661,"stop":2625.617,"duration":30.96}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"I see nothing unfair in their trying to tax the operator on what he has.","start":2625.617,"stop":2630.804,"duration":5.19},{"text":"I do think that if a government plant, whether it's army air base, or whether it's defense plant is located in a town and imposes a burden on that town, I do think that you should not tax someone who does not have something himself for the value of the government property.","start":2630.804,"stop":2652.088,"duration":21.28},{"text":"I think as I suggest here, Borg-Warner has a long-term lease.","start":2652.088,"stop":2656.499,"duration":4.41},{"text":"They are operating for their own private business.","start":2656.499,"stop":2659.098,"duration":2.6},{"text":"We would, admit and uphold the validity of any statute that assessed the value of that leasehold interest which is substantial.","start":2659.098,"stop":2666.419,"duration":7.32},{"text":"In (Inaudible) case this Court held that the lessee had the full, lessee's interest with the full value of the buildings there involved which had a life shorter than lease.","start":2666.419,"stop":2677.055,"duration":10.64},{"text":"I don't know about how the machinery here would work out, how the building would work out.","start":2677.055,"stop":2680.078,"duration":3.02}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If it worked out some sophisticated formula which would gain a large proportion of this tax, do you think it was all right?","start":2680.078,"stop":2687.682,"duration":7.6}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"It because they would be -- not be taxing the government's property because of the government's property they would be taxing the value of something it's non taxable, a taxable person has because of that value.","start":2687.682,"stop":2698.935,"duration":11.25}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You are saying that Michigan in effect said we can't tax this as such, but we've taxed this by saying, in fact it is just as much as it were a tax as such by saying it's a privilege for having it.","start":2698.935,"stop":2711.034,"duration":12.1}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2711.034,"stop":2711.651,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You say that's a crude thing, but a sophisticated formula would be all right.","start":2711.651,"stop":2714.66,"duration":3.01}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"No, not just a sophisticated formula.","start":2714.66,"stop":2715.963,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't mean, I don't mean an invasive one, but one that tried to work out the cash value of having this privilege?","start":2715.963,"stop":2724.083,"duration":8.12}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Of what the lessee had, as a property interest if it is a property tax.","start":2724.083,"stop":2728.993,"duration":4.91},{"text":"In order to – they can have a privilege tax for being an aircraft manufacturer in Michigan, they can charge a privilege tax based on being an aircraft manufacturer.","start":2728.993,"stop":2735.75,"duration":6.76},{"text":"But the tax of privilege tax on being an aircraft manufacturer on government tax again property measured by the value of the government property, it's just too much like taxing a government property.","start":2735.75,"stop":2745.217,"duration":9.47}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But suppose you had another, suppose you had another client alongside Borg plant that was exactly the same in size and construction and that was conducted on it exactly the same kind of an operation.","start":2745.217,"stop":2760.962,"duration":15.74},{"text":"Only it was a private individual and was individually owned.","start":2760.962,"stop":2767.175,"duration":6.21},{"text":"How can you say that it would be unreasonable to charge this man the same if he has a complete use of this property, the same as you would charge the other man?","start":2767.175,"stop":2783.402,"duration":16.23}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"The same way it would be unreasonable tax an air base which was or a post office which is engaged in delivering business, delivering packages and a railway express company engaged in delivering packages, they are both doing the same business and the community cannot tax the post office, it can tax railway express.","start":2783.402,"stop":2801.958,"duration":18.56},{"text":"This, the --you cannot tax that -- and I suppose -- this tax is only on tax against property.","start":2801.958,"stop":2810.091,"duration":8.13},{"text":"It cannot impose a tax on the property.","start":2810.091,"stop":2813.25,"duration":3.16},{"text":"They think that, they think that this is not something of substance, they think there is no -- Michigan treats this as a matter of simply a form that whenever a person is being paid and making a profit for using tax exempt property you can tax him for the whole privilege of that based on the full value of the property.","start":2813.25,"stop":2832.182,"duration":18.93},{"text":"Now Continental is here at will making government property on -- with government machines and a government plant.","start":2832.182,"stop":2840.652,"duration":8.47},{"text":"It is not selling anything commercially.","start":2840.652,"stop":2842.993,"duration":2.34},{"text":"We go over there costs down to the bone, to keep them as low as we can, and there is, they cannot reflect any item of our machinery in that cost figure.","start":2842.993,"stop":2850.968,"duration":7.97},{"text":"Now to say that to impose a tax on the theory this is a privilege of using the government property equal to the tax that they try to impose on Borg-Warner who has a 20 year lease using industrial plant for its own commercial purposes, I think you are not taxing property.","start":2850.968,"stop":2867.24,"duration":16.27},{"text":"I think if you have an aircraft manufacturer's privilege tax, state tax, you can tax that, but you cannot make the use of tax exempt property, a taxable privilege when it's all the lease gives.","start":2867.24,"stop":2880.405,"duration":13.17},{"text":"They have set in the appellee's brief here that the privilege of use is not the lessee's interest.","start":2880.405,"stop":2888.816,"duration":8.41},{"text":"Oh no we are taxing two different things.","start":2888.816,"stop":2891.063,"duration":2.25},{"text":"Of course the Military Leasing Act might limit us the value of the leasehold interest and the (Inaudible) case I might say explicitly in the opinion stated that under the Military Leasing Act, value attributable to a period beyond the lessees interest must be excluded from the tax since it represents the government ownership interest, that's in the footnote discussing this problem.","start":2891.063,"stop":2916.687,"duration":25.62},{"text":"The, they are not taxing the lessee's interest.","start":2916.687,"stop":2921.158,"duration":4.47},{"text":"They are taxing the privilege of use.","start":2921.158,"stop":2922.894,"duration":1.74},{"text":"But what is that, the lease gives that Borg-Warner a privilege of use.","start":2922.894,"stop":2928.318,"duration":5.42},{"text":"The only privilege of use he has is that defined in the lease, it's the same thing.","start":2928.318,"stop":2934.331,"duration":6.01},{"text":"Now there maybe, we may have an occasion when the legal incidence of tax makes a difference, but surely calling the right which the lessee has to the use plant by virtue of the lease calling that a privilege of use doesn't make any difference, it is the lessee's interest.","start":2934.331,"stop":2950.738,"duration":16.41},{"text":"He has no other interest in that plant other than the lease he gives him, he has no other right to use it, no other privilege to use that plant other than the lessee' and other that what the lease gives him and Congress has said that under the Military Leasing Act the lessee's interest the value of it -- clear we think, the legislative history has the value of that interest, there is a limit (Inaudible) to tax and we submit that --","start":2950.738,"stop":2972.708,"duration":21.97}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Fisher if that was so would the value of that interest be a constant over the period of the lease?","start":2972.708,"stop":2981.486,"duration":8.78}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"I would think not, but I would say that a leasehold interest is something that is regularly appraised in condemnation cases, every condemnation case --","start":2981.486,"stop":2991.045,"duration":9.56}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I mean probably it'd be of greater value at the first year then the --","start":2991.045,"stop":2996.769,"duration":5.72}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2996.769,"stop":2997.53,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Then (Inaudible) doesn't help the municipality in anyway does it?","start":2997.53,"stop":3001.696,"duration":4.17}]},{"speakerName":"Roger D. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the private, it may not help them very much, in the Congress and in fact as the Continental plant they are currently receiving for in lieu payment by act of Congress and the school district is receiving until that time, they've receiving at least for three years they received payments based on the impact of this plant on their school system.","start":3001.696,"stop":3021.743,"duration":20.05},{"text":"The equities, then they've decided to measure the -- Congress has decided to measure the aids of the Orchard View School District by the number of children whose parents work in the government plant.","start":3021.743,"stop":3032.178,"duration":10.43},{"text":"Orchard View School District has decided they want to measure that payment by the value of the entire government plan.","start":3032.178,"stop":3037.235,"duration":5.06},{"text":"I think when a conflict comes between the standard which Congress has set by legislation dealing with this very school district among all school district here, federally impacted area, I think that the congressional standard controls, they clearly can control.","start":3037.235,"stop":3052.289,"duration":15.05},{"text":"Our basic point is that in the Borg-Warner case that's covered by the implied immunity, but explicitly by the Military Leasing Act and that in the Muskegon case involving Continental.","start":3052.289,"stop":3064.335,"duration":12.05},{"text":"The Continental interest which is at will (Inaudible) at will to make government property on a government plant, does not subject the entire value of the defense plan owned by the United States there to a greater tax than the Muskegon, There is no greater interest in Continental, they have a less of interest than Borg-Warner had, and we believe that Congress in legislating understood only if lesser interest could be taxed, only the lessee interest.","start":3064.335,"stop":3094.109,"duration":29.77},{"text":"I'll save the balance of my time for rebuttal.","start":3094.109,"stop":3099.091,"duration":4.98}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. O'Connor.","start":3099.091,"stop":3106.703,"duration":7.61}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, Associate Justices, may I please the Court.","start":3106.703,"stop":3112.491,"duration":5.79},{"text":"I think I would like to at the outset of this case, clarify the contentions of the parties and then analyze this Act 189 which is unique and peculiar and is special legislation but not aimed at United States property but aimed at the purpose of eliminating a discrimination between lessees of users, lessee and users of private and public property.","start":3112.491,"stop":3141.593,"duration":29.1},{"text":"First of all a contention of the United States is that Act 189 imposes an ad velorem tax on the United States, since the full value of the property is used as a measure of the tax.","start":3141.593,"stop":3157.514,"duration":15.92},{"text":"It is the City of Detroit's contention that Act 189 imposes a specific tax, not a property tax, on the tax exempt property in connection with the business conducted for a profit and that clause is very important and that such a tax under such cases as Plummer versus Coler, Home Insurance Company, these all are decided by this Court.","start":3157.514,"stop":3183.655,"duration":26.14},{"text":"Home Insurance Company versus New York, Educational Films Corporation, Pacific versus Johnson, Plynth versus (Inaudible), Tracy and last but not least Esso Corporation.","start":3183.655,"stop":3195.387,"duration":11.73}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. O'Connor what's the rate that's supplied, is it the local Detroit rate, tax rate?","start":3195.387,"stop":3201.437,"duration":6.05}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes it is.","start":3201.437,"stop":3202.517,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And is that arrived at by including in the ratables the values of these properties?","start":3202.517,"stop":3211.034,"duration":8.52}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3211.034,"stop":3212.658,"duration":1.62},{"text":"But it must be born in mind of course that this is tax on a privilege and property of the United States maybe used as a measure of a tax on the privilege as provided under these cases.","start":3212.658,"stop":3225.14,"duration":12.48},{"text":"Now a privilege tax does not have to be proportional to the values of the same tax.","start":3225.14,"stop":3231.314,"duration":6.17},{"text":"The same tax in most of instances of course is the privilege of using the property.","start":3231.314,"stop":3236.345,"duration":5.03},{"text":"Congress, or rather the legislature of Michigan, to accomplish its purpose, namely to avoid discrimination between lessees of users and of private and public property and put them on an equal footing, may choose any sum it wishes, providing it's reasonable to accomplish the result intended.","start":3236.345,"stop":3259.744,"duration":23.4},{"text":"It so happened that in this case --","start":3259.744,"stop":3261.664,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Any private property pay a real estate tax?","start":3261.664,"stop":3265.318,"duration":3.65}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"The lessee of private property does pay a real estate tax, either in the rent charge or in addition with the rent, in consideration of a reduction in rent (Inaudible)","start":3265.318,"stop":3278.009,"duration":12.69}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"As far as Detroit is concerned, Detroit gets no real estate tax from the lessee though, does it?","start":3278.009,"stop":3286.139,"duration":8.13}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Well in this particular case, yes it would in this particular case under this Act.","start":3286.139,"stop":3290.624,"duration":4.48}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No I mean a private, a lessee of private property (Inaudible) no real estate tax for the City of Detroit, does he?","start":3290.624,"stop":3298.091,"duration":7.47}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but the lessee by virtue or leasing property from a private lessor, that lessee either pays the tax on that profit, which is included in the rent charge or is paid in addition --","start":3298.091,"stop":3314.999,"duration":16.91}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes but as far municipal revenues are concerned, raised by taxes, no part of those revenues are contributed by lessees of private property.","start":3314.999,"stop":3329.533,"duration":14.53}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Frankly I'm not certain of that at this point Your Honor.","start":3329.533,"stop":3332.464,"duration":2.93}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well the owner of the property I take it pays the real estate taxes.","start":3332.464,"stop":3335.887,"duration":3.42}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"The owner of the property pays the real estate taxes.","start":3335.887,"stop":3338.391,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Although it's from him and to him that Detroit looks for the payment of the taxes on that profit.","start":3338.391,"stop":3346.312,"duration":7.92}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Under general ad valorem of property taxes yes, but under this special Act that is not the situation.","start":3346.312,"stop":3351.756,"duration":5.44}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well the thing is --","start":3351.756,"stop":3352.287,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"This Act has --","start":3352.287,"stop":3352.872,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"As a practical matter you told me that the values of these publically owned properties where they are leased enter into the general ratables upon -- which formed the base from which the tax rate is computed.","start":3352.872,"stop":3367.491,"duration":14.62}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah that's --","start":3367.491,"stop":3368.461,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The practical effect of this is that the lessee of this publically owned property does pay the real estate tax upon that property.","start":3368.461,"stop":3380.856,"duration":12.4}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"No it does not.","start":3380.856,"stop":3381.785,"duration":0.93},{"text":"It pays the tax on the privilege of using that property.","start":3381.785,"stop":3384.755,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well that's the words you use, but the practical effect of it is that he is paying the taxes on the property.","start":3384.755,"stop":3391.463,"duration":6.71}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3391.463,"stop":3391.707,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If the ratables of the values of property goes into ratables and the tax rate is struck on ratables which include the value for those properties, why isn't he paying the real estate (Inaudible)","start":3391.707,"stop":3403.585,"duration":11.88}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Well if you desire to take that position, if Your Honor please I can understand --","start":3403.585,"stop":3408.758,"duration":5.17}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not deciding to take any position.","start":3408.758,"stop":3410.374,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I can understand the practical affect of it, yes.","start":3410.374,"stop":3413.236,"duration":2.86},{"text":"What you say is possibly true from the practical effect of it, but when you have a privilege tax, you can do that very thing, by you using the government's property as a measure of the tax.","start":3413.236,"stop":3425.704,"duration":12.47},{"text":"Now that is the only way, if Your Honors please, that the State of Michigan could eliminate the discrimination between lessees of private and public property by fixing some sum equal to the amount of tax paid on the real estate.","start":3425.704,"stop":3444.384,"duration":18.68},{"text":"Now the fact that it's equal to the amount paid on the real estate does not necessarily mean that the tax is on the real estate of the United States.","start":3444.384,"stop":3453.624,"duration":9.24},{"text":"It could have been, Michigan legislature could have imposed a larger for the privilege used.","start":3453.624,"stop":3460.828,"duration":7.2},{"text":"Now I'm giving, digressing some what --","start":3460.828,"stop":3461.774,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you this, the real effect of this is, whether it's right or wrong, that Michigan has a use tax which implies that nobody in the state, except those who have leased government tax exempt property.","start":3461.774,"stop":3480.305,"duration":18.53}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"This Act applies to tax exempt property used in connection with the business, conducted for profit.","start":3480.305,"stop":3488.791,"duration":8.49}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The affect is if you have a (Inaudible) which applies, maybe it's all right, (Inaudible) did you have an Act which the legislature passed, for the use tax upon industrial uses of government property, for the use of government property?","start":3488.791,"stop":3508.823,"duration":20.03}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes in connection with the business conducted for profit.","start":3508.823,"stop":3511.82,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It applies for no one else in the state except that.","start":3511.82,"stop":3515.749,"duration":3.93}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it applies to the United States property as well as any properties owned by the State of Michigan or any of its political subdivisions, when leased or used in connection with a business conducted for the profit to a private individual, corporation or association.","start":3515.749,"stop":3534.994,"duration":19.25}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any tax imposed on?","start":3534.994,"stop":3537.227,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"The tax is imposed upon the lessee or user of the property, for the privilege of using that property.","start":3537.227,"stop":3543.531,"duration":6.3}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Are there any people, any industrial companies in the City of Detroit, this is Detroit taxes?","start":3543.531,"stop":3548.997,"duration":5.47}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, now --","start":3548.997,"stop":3550.03,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Are there any uses of properties that are of state property that have to pay this tax?","start":3550.03,"stop":3556.066,"duration":6.04}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, first of all let me refer Your Honor to the record, page 97 thereof, which is the personal property assessment roll for 1954 involved --","start":3556.066,"stop":3573.572,"duration":17.51}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Page what?","start":3573.572,"stop":3574.682,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Page 97.","start":3574.682,"stop":3581.044,"duration":6.36},{"text":"Now, Your Honors will note the first parcel of property appearing on that assessment roll is the Borg-Warner property.","start":3581.044,"stop":3591.793,"duration":10.75},{"text":"Your Honors will further note in connection with the Borg-Warner property --","start":3591.793,"stop":3595.342,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is that?","start":3595.342,"stop":3596.305,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is this pulled --","start":3596.305,"stop":3597.331,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Page 97.","start":3597.331,"stop":3598.936,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Of what?","start":3598.936,"stop":3599.732,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Of the record.","start":3599.732,"stop":3600.552,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh all right.","start":3600.552,"stop":3602.6,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"MI'm sorry Your Honor.","start":3602.6,"stop":3607.147,"duration":4.55},{"text":"In the Borg-Warner case, that's the brown, that's a brown book.","start":3607.147,"stop":3616.969,"duration":9.82}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Brown record in number 26.","start":3616.969,"stop":3617.919,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Black you have that --","start":3617.919,"stop":3619.524,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes I got it.","start":3619.524,"stop":3623.836,"duration":4.31}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"You have it Mr. Justice Whitaker, that's correct.","start":3623.836,"stop":3626.766,"duration":2.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right, what page was it?","start":3626.766,"stop":3628.498,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Page 97.","start":3628.498,"stop":3629.522,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":3629.522,"stop":3632.797,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Now you will note on that personal property assessment roll of the Borg-Warner property is the first parcel appearing thereon.","start":3632.797,"stop":3641.38,"duration":8.58},{"text":"You will note also that right next to that name appears the words, Act 189 PA 1953, leased land bill.","start":3641.38,"stop":3655.168,"duration":13.79},{"text":"That applies in cases of all the four parcels on that assessment roll.","start":3655.168,"stop":3659.791,"duration":4.62},{"text":"Now the reason that was put on there was to distinguish it from ordinary personal property put on a personal property assessment roll and that which would be subject to the ordinary provisions of the statutes concerning personal property if it were not for that notation placed around calling all persons to attention -- the attention of all persons to the fact that that property is being leased under Act 189.","start":3659.791,"stop":3690.046,"duration":30.25},{"text":"Now Jefferson, the next parcel of property which is written in ink, Feldman Mitchell looks like 105 but it's actually 905 (Inaudible), that parcel of real estate is owned by the State of Michigan and it is leased to Mr. Feldman for a parking lot.","start":3690.046,"stop":3720.087,"duration":30.04},{"text":"The next parcel of real estate which appears in the name of Houston Hayes Land Company belongs to the City of Highland Park and that parcel of real estate is leased to Houston Hayes for a customer parking lot in connection with its business conducted for profit.","start":3720.087,"stop":3742.922,"duration":22.84},{"text":"The next parcel of property appearing on the assessment roll is Jefferson Corporation.","start":3742.922,"stop":3749.122,"duration":6.2},{"text":"That case is -- the property involved in that case is owned by the United States.","start":3749.122,"stop":3755.664,"duration":6.54},{"text":"There is a suit pending on that case presently pending in the City of Detroit awaiting the outcome and decision of this Borg-Warner case.","start":3755.664,"stop":3766.296,"duration":10.63}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What's that last one?","start":3766.296,"stop":3768.099,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"The last one Feldman Mitchell --","start":3768.099,"stop":3771.118,"duration":3.02}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3771.118,"stop":3771.404,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"There was error made there judge and you can see where it's transpired up.","start":3771.404,"stop":3776.789,"duration":5.39}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What was that error?","start":3776.789,"stop":3778.984,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"That was a parcel of property owned by the State of Michigan and leased to Mr. Feldman for a parking lot in connection with the business conducted for profit.","start":3778.984,"stop":3789.088,"duration":10.1}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3789.088,"stop":3790.698,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Same as the second.","start":3790.698,"stop":3791.834,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words you had a duplication?","start":3791.834,"stop":3792.857,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes that's right, they made a mistake apparently down on the lower or rather originally it was listed in Silverware Company, you'll notice the last, the last name appearing thereon, well that was a management company.","start":3792.857,"stop":3805.565,"duration":12.71}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Then what you are saying is that you have a tax, a use tax on – that you described, which contains within its classification not merely leased property or the use of property leased for the United States, leased for Michigan on any of its subsidiaries.","start":3805.565,"stop":3826.725,"duration":21.16}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct Your Honor.","start":3826.725,"stop":3828.841,"duration":2.12},{"text":"So it doesn't necessarily and it doesn't aim at the United States property in particular whether it includes all other properties of the State of Michigan or any of its political subdivisions leased in connection with the business conducted for profit.","start":3828.841,"stop":3844.587,"duration":15.75}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And the property which is leased from the State of Michigan based on the same basis, the same rate as though it was leased from the government.","start":3844.587,"stop":3855.116,"duration":10.53}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes, yes.","start":3855.116,"stop":3857.424,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"One of these properties was exempt, was exempted properties -- exempted under Michigan law, one of them was municipally exempted, would you mind stating in a word what the basis of municipal exemption was?","start":3857.424,"stop":3871.254,"duration":13.83}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"One of these parcels appearing on this roll?","start":3871.254,"stop":3872.778,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes didn't you say that one of them was exempted by some municipal -- under some municipal was leased -- property leased by a city which enjoyed exemption, one of these things.","start":3872.778,"stop":3883.908,"duration":11.13}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Houston Hayes.","start":3883.908,"stop":3885.44,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3885.44,"stop":3888.044,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Houston Hayes, I understood you to say that they leased it from the city of, City of Detroit or State of Michigan or whatever it was and then under Michigan law that property is exempt from taxation as to --","start":3888.044,"stop":3898.038,"duration":9.99}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Highland Park.","start":3898.038,"stop":3899.075,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes Highland Park --","start":3899.075,"stop":3900.756,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that a city?","start":3900.756,"stop":3901.871,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes that's a city Your Honor and --","start":3901.871,"stop":3903.526,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And the property was exempt, wasn't it?","start":3903.526,"stop":3905.174,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"And it was owned by Highland Park?","start":3905.174,"stop":3907.464,"duration":2.29}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Why was it exempt?","start":3907.464,"stop":3909.509,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Why was it exempt?","start":3909.509,"stop":3910.067,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, what --","start":3910.067,"stop":3910.764,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Because it was owned by the city of Highland park.","start":3910.764,"stop":3914.159,"duration":3.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":3914.159,"stop":3915.792,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3915.792,"stop":3931.417,"duration":15.63}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3931.417,"stop":3932.888,"duration":1.47},{"text":"That's right that lessee would pay the tax because the charitable institution would not be using it for those purposes.","start":3932.888,"stop":3940.099,"duration":7.21},{"text":"It would be leasing it out to a private person in connection with a business conducted for profit and rightfully they should be taxed.","start":3940.099,"stop":3948.079,"duration":7.98}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So you are saying --","start":3948.079,"stop":3948.465,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Those lessees should bear some of the burden.","start":3948.465,"stop":3950.346,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So that you are going to say this is not an evasion for hitting federally exempt property, is that --","start":3950.346,"stop":3957.653,"duration":7.31}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"I say that very thing, Your Honor.","start":3957.653,"stop":3959.985,"duration":2.33},{"text":"Now you may recall in some of these other cases the Macallen versus Massachusetts, Milwaukee case that the Court said the tax may very well be valid even though it might incidentally affect bonds providing us – not aim at those bonds of the United States but was passed with a different intent and purpose.","start":3959.985,"stop":3986.811,"duration":26.83},{"text":"Now the intent and purpose here as I have explained of the legislature of the State of Michigan was to impose this tax to seek to avoid discrimination between lessees of public and private properties.","start":3986.811,"stop":3998.999,"duration":12.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But you could, you could say these about the Macallen case --","start":3998.999,"stop":4003.394,"duration":4.39}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes I am sure.","start":4003.394,"stop":4004.166,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes you could say many things about that.","start":4004.166,"stop":4006.205,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose that any of the land that is given -- allotted to the State of Michigan such as school lands or other lands if the state leased those properties the same tax would apply to them, would it?","start":4006.205,"stop":4020.882,"duration":14.68}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Except there are certain -- there is a certain exception in the act and the state supported educational institutions are not subject to the tax.","start":4020.882,"stop":4028.407,"duration":7.53}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"No, we are talking about for purposes like this, taking about for manufacturing plants or anything of that kind.","start":4028.407,"stop":4035.803,"duration":7.4}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":4035.803,"stop":4036.117,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"If you leased any of those school lands, the lessee would be subject to this tax just the same as --","start":4036.117,"stop":4043.207,"duration":7.09}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct as long he is using them for that purpose.","start":4043.207,"stop":4047.105,"duration":3.9},{"text":"Now there is a vast distinction as Your Honors may well know, between a privilege tax and an ad valorem tax on the property itself.","start":4047.105,"stop":4056.541,"duration":9.44},{"text":"An ad valorem tax goes on ad infinitum whether the property is being using or not.","start":4056.541,"stop":4065.015,"duration":8.47},{"text":"In connection with Act 189, as long -- when the property is no longer used then there is no tax imposed under this act.","start":4065.015,"stop":4075.93,"duration":10.91},{"text":"It has to be used in connection with the business conducted for profit.","start":4075.93,"stop":4080.642,"duration":4.71}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Aside from the difference in name between this tax and the other taxes you had put us through, is there any valid distinction?","start":4080.642,"stop":4091.203,"duration":10.56}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes in this case we contend this is a privilege tax in the Murray prior there too that involved a different statute entirely of the City of Detroit or a charter provision statute, both, which was the regular ad valorem personal property tax statute which provides for a lien on property.","start":4091.203,"stop":4115.892,"duration":24.69},{"text":"This --","start":4115.892,"stop":4116.111,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) precisely the same rate of taxation that's in this county, does it not?","start":4116.111,"stop":4121.528,"duration":5.42}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes it does Mr. Justice Black.","start":4121.528,"stop":4123.273,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And does the same in everything except the preference for which it's clear to be levied.","start":4123.273,"stop":4130.466,"duration":7.19}]},{"speakerName":"Roger P. O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes that was an ordinary ad valorem general property tax statute on the property itself.","start":4130.466,"stop":4135.747,"duration":5.28},{"text":"This is special legislature which is passed for taxing the privilege of using and not aimed at the United States property in any (Inaudible) whatsoever.","start":4135.747,"stop":4146.298,"duration":10.55},{"text":"Now --","start":4146.298,"stop":4149.488,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess, we'll recess now Mr. O'Connor.","start":4149.488,"stop":4154.213,"duration":4.72}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Nov 14, 1957","petitioner":"","respondent":"","docket":"26","citation":"355 US 466 (1958)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/355/466","lowerCourt":"","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Mar 3, 1958"}